00:02:59.580 --> 00:03:02.460
[Amit Varma]: Srinath, welcome to the scene in the unseen.

00:03:02.460 --> 00:03:03.460
[Amit Varma]: Thanks so much.

00:03:03.460 --> 00:03:08.140
[Amit Varma]: Srinath, you're the first historian on the scene in the unseen and your history is quite

00:03:08.140 --> 00:03:11.620
[Amit Varma]: interesting itself because you had mentioned that you were into theoretical physics and

00:03:11.620 --> 00:03:14.900
[Amit Varma]: were thinking of getting a PhD in theoretical physics, but then you joined the Rajputana

00:03:14.900 --> 00:03:21.140
[Amit Varma]: Rifles and then you spent a few years there and then you got into becoming a historian.

00:03:21.140 --> 00:03:23.060
[Amit Varma]: So how did how did that happen?

00:03:23.060 --> 00:03:28.860
[Guest]: Well, as an undergraduate, I was studying physics and hoping to do doctoral work there.

00:03:28.860 --> 00:03:32.580
[Guest]: But you know, with things like theoretical physics or pure mathematics, either you're

00:03:32.580 --> 00:03:33.580
[Guest]: really good or you're no good.

00:03:33.580 --> 00:03:38.020
[Guest]: You know, you can't be there's no such thing as a middling sort of physicist in some ways.

00:03:38.020 --> 00:03:42.340
[Guest]: And I kind of understood pretty quickly that I was on the no good side of things.

00:03:42.340 --> 00:03:47.540
[Guest]: So decided to drop the sciences but had very little idea what else to do.

00:03:47.540 --> 00:03:51.260
[Guest]: And I had a couple of friends from college who had signed up for the short service commission

00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:55.660
[Guest]: and that seemed to me to be an interesting way to spend a few years, you know, get to

00:03:55.660 --> 00:04:00.060
[Guest]: see places I hadn't and then hopefully make up my mind about what I wanted to do.

00:04:00.060 --> 00:04:03.820
[Guest]: So I joined the Indian Army and got commissioned to the Rajputana Rifles.

00:04:03.820 --> 00:04:04.820
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:04:04.820 --> 00:04:08.860
[Amit Varma]: And tell me something about how you got drawn to history per se, like, were you always a

00:04:08.860 --> 00:04:12.160
[Amit Varma]: keen reader of sort of books of history and then decided that, hey, I want to do this

00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:14.980
[Amit Varma]: myself or was there something which kind of triggered that?

00:04:14.980 --> 00:04:19.300
[Guest]: Well, I mean, I was always very interested in politics from the time I was a student

00:04:19.300 --> 00:04:21.660
[Guest]: growing up in India, in some ways, you couldn't help it.

00:04:21.660 --> 00:04:24.420
[Guest]: Early 90s was a highly political time in this country.

00:04:24.420 --> 00:04:28.100
[Guest]: And I was very interested in sort of politics.

00:04:28.100 --> 00:04:31.700
[Guest]: I was fortunate that when I was a teenager, I was surrounded by people who gave me a lot

00:04:31.700 --> 00:04:34.580
[Guest]: of exposure to learning, thinking about politics.

00:04:34.580 --> 00:04:37.960
[Guest]: And of course, history was always a way into that.

00:04:37.960 --> 00:04:41.620
[Guest]: But I must confess that I didn't get around to doing any serious sort of study of history

00:04:41.620 --> 00:04:46.300
[Guest]: till such time actually I was halfway through my tenure in the army, when it became interesting

00:04:46.300 --> 00:04:51.540
[Guest]: to me that, you know, some of the things that I was sort of actually doing had, you know,

00:04:51.540 --> 00:04:55.820
[Guest]: military history and the history of war per se, particular caught my fancy.

00:04:55.820 --> 00:04:58.300
[Guest]: And that is how I started getting interested in it.

00:04:58.300 --> 00:05:02.820
[Guest]: You know, when I look back, I think the one history book which possibly had the most impact

00:05:02.820 --> 00:05:07.460
[Guest]: on me was something that I never read as a piece of history in that sense is this book

00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:11.380
[Guest]: called The Making of the Atomic Bomb by Richard Rhodes, which won a Pulitzer Prize in 1989,

00:05:11.380 --> 00:05:12.380
[Guest]: if I'm not mistaken.

00:05:12.380 --> 00:05:17.260
[Guest]: And an uncle of mine who used to go to the United States quite often back in those days,

00:05:17.260 --> 00:05:19.460
[Guest]: actually got me a copy and I must have read it several times.

00:05:19.460 --> 00:05:20.860
[Guest]: I still have it on my shelves.

00:05:20.860 --> 00:05:22.540
[Amit Varma]: And I still think it's a great book.

00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:26.220
[Amit Varma]: Well, so that's that's a book that listeners can get from Amazon right away.

00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:28.140
[Amit Varma]: And being a historian, what does it involve?

00:05:28.140 --> 00:05:32.180
[Amit Varma]: Like we live in an age, of course, where you don't only have facts, you also have alternative

00:05:32.180 --> 00:05:35.340
[Amit Varma]: facts and you have all kinds of narratives being peddled.

00:05:35.340 --> 00:05:40.060
[Amit Varma]: So at one level, there is, of course, the sense that the layman might have that, oh,

00:05:40.060 --> 00:05:41.320
[Amit Varma]: we know what happened in history.

00:05:41.320 --> 00:05:44.980
[Amit Varma]: Why do we need to, you know, kind of go back and look for, you know, what are we really

00:05:44.980 --> 00:05:46.460
[Amit Varma]: looking for?

00:05:46.460 --> 00:05:50.500
[Amit Varma]: And at the other level, there's almost a sense that now, though, it doesn't matter.

00:05:50.500 --> 00:05:52.420
[Amit Varma]: Anybody can say anything, anything goes.

00:05:52.420 --> 00:05:53.660
[Amit Varma]: So what does it really involve?

00:05:53.660 --> 00:05:58.580
[Amit Varma]: Like, when you choose a particular project, do you start with a fascination over, say,

00:05:58.580 --> 00:06:00.700
[Amit Varma]: a particular historical character?

00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:03.820
[Amit Varma]: Or do you feel that there is a shortcoming with some specific narrative?

00:06:03.820 --> 00:06:07.140
[Amit Varma]: Or do you feel that there are gaps in this narrative and I need to fill them?

00:06:07.140 --> 00:06:08.140
[Guest]: How does it?

00:06:08.140 --> 00:06:11.500
[Guest]: Yeah, I think it's more the latter rather than the former, at least in my case.

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:16.460
[Guest]: And the way that typically historians and people who are sort of studying history professionally

00:06:16.460 --> 00:06:21.260
[Guest]: tend to sort of approach is to say that, listen, you want to take a look at some particular

00:06:21.260 --> 00:06:26.700
[Guest]: question and then try and, you know, get a grip on it by looking at historical materials,

00:06:26.700 --> 00:06:27.700
[Guest]: right?

00:06:27.700 --> 00:06:32.780
[Guest]: So, in a sense, what we tend to think of as being taken for granted are things which are

00:06:32.780 --> 00:06:33.960
[Guest]: constantly up for revision.

00:06:33.960 --> 00:06:38.700
[Guest]: So in that sense, you know, there's a great Dutch historian called Peter Gale, who said

00:06:38.700 --> 00:06:40.660
[Guest]: that history is an argument without end.

00:06:40.660 --> 00:06:43.580
[Guest]: And I think that's a very good way of thinking about the subject, which is to say that you're

00:06:43.580 --> 00:06:47.820
[Guest]: constantly approaching the past with new perspectives, because the questions that you're interested

00:06:47.820 --> 00:06:50.420
[Guest]: about the past are always determined by your present.

00:06:50.420 --> 00:06:54.460
[Guest]: So it's your current politics, it's your current sort of social interests that in some ways,

00:06:54.460 --> 00:06:55.580
[Guest]: trigger your interest in the past.

00:06:55.580 --> 00:06:59.300
[Guest]: That is how the study of history continuously evolves over a period of time.

00:06:59.300 --> 00:07:01.980
[Guest]: And when you're looking at new themes, you're also looking at new evidence.

00:07:01.980 --> 00:07:04.740
[Guest]: So you're looking at new archives, you're looking at new texts.

00:07:04.740 --> 00:07:10.060
[Guest]: So in that sense, you know, it is rarely the case that in history, people tend to disagree

00:07:10.060 --> 00:07:11.180
[Guest]: about brute facts, right?

00:07:11.180 --> 00:07:15.500
[Guest]: I mean, of course, you always have some debates about how valuable this or that piece of evidence

00:07:15.500 --> 00:07:16.500
[Guest]: is.

00:07:16.500 --> 00:07:18.740
[Guest]: But what you're looking for is a fit between argument and evidence.

00:07:18.740 --> 00:07:23.540
[Guest]: And in that sense, it's, you know, history, like the other social sciences, is continually

00:07:23.540 --> 00:07:28.260
[Guest]: determined by your sort of current location and your interests, social location, political

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:29.260
[Guest]: location matters a lot.

00:07:29.260 --> 00:07:33.820
[Amit Varma]: And I guess it's necessarily true that every simple narrative is fundamentally wrong because

00:07:33.820 --> 00:07:34.820
[Amit Varma]: of its simplicity.

00:07:34.820 --> 00:07:39.580
[Amit Varma]: And there are layers and layers and you essentially kind of, so you know, before we get to the

00:07:39.580 --> 00:07:44.140
[Amit Varma]: subject at hand for this episode, what does your work then really involve?

00:07:44.140 --> 00:07:47.140
[Amit Varma]: Like when you when you begin a project, you already sort of have a broad narrative in

00:07:47.140 --> 00:07:49.220
[Amit Varma]: mind and you're looking for evidence that confirms it?

00:07:49.220 --> 00:07:52.620
[Amit Varma]: Or are you just saying that, hey, this is interesting, let me go a little deeper and

00:07:52.620 --> 00:07:53.740
[Amit Varma]: find out.

00:07:53.740 --> 00:07:55.160
[Amit Varma]: And then like, how does it work?

00:07:55.160 --> 00:07:59.340
[Amit Varma]: What kind of like, when you talk about, you know, going into the archives, what are these

00:07:59.340 --> 00:08:00.340
[Amit Varma]: archives?

00:08:00.340 --> 00:08:01.340
[Amit Varma]: How do you find this material?

00:08:01.340 --> 00:08:02.340
[Amit Varma]: How do you approach it?

00:08:02.340 --> 00:08:05.220
[Guest]: So let me give you a sort of explain this using a concrete example.

00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:09.340
[Guest]: So my one of the books I wrote, actually, my second book was a history of the creation

00:08:09.340 --> 00:08:10.340
[Guest]: of Bangladesh in 1971.

00:08:10.340 --> 00:08:11.340
[Guest]: Right.

00:08:11.340 --> 00:08:15.820
[Guest]: So for a project like that, basically, I was actually working on a another earlier project

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:21.260
[Guest]: that led me to find a bunch of papers, which completely astonished me for the depth of

00:08:21.260 --> 00:08:23.740
[Guest]: material that they had on the Bangladesh crisis.

00:08:23.740 --> 00:08:27.500
[Guest]: And these were the papers of P.N. Huxer, the principal secretary to Mrs. Indira Gandhi,

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:30.380
[Guest]: who was a very key figure during the 1971 crisis.

00:08:30.380 --> 00:08:34.620
[Guest]: So what I got really was a bunch of materials which suggested to me that, hey, there's so

00:08:34.620 --> 00:08:39.620
[Guest]: much in here that is not known, that could be used to tell a much more better informed

00:08:39.620 --> 00:08:40.620
[Guest]: and a better story.

00:08:40.620 --> 00:08:42.620
[Guest]: But of course, you can't do it with just one set of materials, right?

00:08:42.620 --> 00:08:45.920
[Guest]: So then for several years, I started researching it.

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:49.660
[Guest]: And the more I went into the subject, it seemed to me that, you know, just a lot of stuff

00:08:49.660 --> 00:08:53.820
[Guest]: had been written primarily from either the Indian or the Bangladeshi or the Pakistani

00:08:53.820 --> 00:08:54.820
[Guest]: perspective.

00:08:54.820 --> 00:08:58.340
[Guest]: But what was very interesting to me was the global dimension of the crisis, how so many

00:08:58.340 --> 00:09:02.620
[Guest]: other players who are in some ways geographically remote, were nevertheless politically very

00:09:02.620 --> 00:09:05.540
[Guest]: involved and how all of that came through.

00:09:05.540 --> 00:09:08.620
[Guest]: As I dug deeper into the subject, it became apparent to me that we're not only talking

00:09:08.620 --> 00:09:11.700
[Guest]: about states who are involved, but also other kinds of people, the cultural influences,

00:09:11.700 --> 00:09:16.860
[Guest]: you know, the concept of Bangladesh in 1971, you know, someone like Allen Ginsberg writing

00:09:16.860 --> 00:09:19.700
[Guest]: the famous poem in the New York Times and so on, right?

00:09:19.700 --> 00:09:24.780
[Guest]: So what it then led me to was to basically take a very different approach to thinking

00:09:24.780 --> 00:09:28.160
[Guest]: about the creation of Bangladesh, which in turn then led me to start questioning some

00:09:28.160 --> 00:09:29.420
[Guest]: fundamental assumptions, right?

00:09:29.420 --> 00:09:32.820
[Guest]: That in some ways, the creation of Bangladesh was inevitable because these two geographical

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:33.820
[Guest]: parts were separate.

00:09:33.820 --> 00:09:35.120
[Guest]: Actually, not true at all.

00:09:35.120 --> 00:09:36.540
[Guest]: In fact, it was much more contingent.

00:09:36.540 --> 00:09:40.100
[Guest]: And that was one of the main arguments of the book that if things had not taken the

00:09:40.100 --> 00:09:44.740
[Guest]: turn that they did in the late 1960s, and for reasons which are not specific to Bangladesh,

00:09:44.740 --> 00:09:49.100
[Guest]: but for a global conjuncture, you may never have had this crisis coming out, right?

00:09:49.100 --> 00:09:53.660
[Guest]: Which is a bit of an unsettling proposition to make, particularly for Bangladeshis.

00:09:53.660 --> 00:09:57.140
[Guest]: But that's the way I think history moves is that you start with some piece of evidence,

00:09:57.140 --> 00:10:00.980
[Guest]: you see how it fits with what the received narratives are, then you come up with a different

00:10:00.980 --> 00:10:02.900
[Guest]: way of explaining this stuff.

00:10:02.900 --> 00:10:04.900
[Amit Varma]: And then you sort of present an alternative sort of narrative.

00:10:04.900 --> 00:10:06.380
[Amit Varma]: Sadanand That's fascinating.

00:10:06.380 --> 00:10:09.420
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one day we should do an episode on 1971.

00:10:09.420 --> 00:10:13.060
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, the whole Bangladesh thing sort of forms part of the narrative of this book.

00:10:13.060 --> 00:10:17.260
[Amit Varma]: Your latest book is called The Most Dangerous Place, Colonial History of the United States

00:10:17.260 --> 00:10:19.180
[Amit Varma]: in South Asia.

00:10:19.180 --> 00:10:24.740
[Amit Varma]: And what the book looks at is essentially evolving American attitudes towards this region,

00:10:24.740 --> 00:10:28.940
[Amit Varma]: which we call South Asia over the last more than 200 years.

00:10:28.940 --> 00:10:32.180
[Amit Varma]: And you know, how did you arrive at this kind of specific project?

00:10:32.180 --> 00:10:34.820
[Amit Varma]: And I'm also intrigued by the title, The Most Dangerous Place in the World.

00:10:34.820 --> 00:10:37.380
[Guest]: Dr. Sanjay Gupta Yeah, so the project in some ways is, you

00:10:37.380 --> 00:10:42.440
[Guest]: know, for various other projects that I've been doing, especially for the three previous

00:10:42.440 --> 00:10:46.620
[Guest]: books that I wrote, including this book on the creation of Bangladesh, I had been visiting

00:10:46.620 --> 00:10:50.820
[Guest]: various American archives, the National Archives of the United States, various presidential

00:10:50.820 --> 00:10:54.380
[Guest]: libraries to do research over the last 15 years or so.

00:10:54.380 --> 00:10:57.900
[Guest]: So at some point, you know, about three or four years ago, it struck me that I just have

00:10:57.900 --> 00:11:03.860
[Guest]: so much materials that I could still use to sort of tell a story of American involvement

00:11:03.860 --> 00:11:04.900
[Guest]: in this region.

00:11:04.900 --> 00:11:08.660
[Guest]: And it's again, it struck me that much of the narrative and much of the good scholarship

00:11:08.660 --> 00:11:13.580
[Guest]: and the good books that we have are primarily focusing either on very specific periods like

00:11:13.580 --> 00:11:18.340
[Guest]: the Cold War, they tend to focus on the high politics, which is to say, you know, US India,

00:11:18.340 --> 00:11:22.260
[Guest]: US Pakistan relationships, or they tend to focus on one sets of relationship, right?

00:11:22.260 --> 00:11:26.740
[Guest]: I mean, it's about how the United States dealt with India, and so on and so forth.

00:11:26.740 --> 00:11:30.740
[Guest]: And it seemed to me that what we needed was a book which was at once broader, and longer

00:11:30.740 --> 00:11:33.340
[Guest]: in historical chronological scope.

00:11:33.340 --> 00:11:36.820
[Guest]: And you know, I had already written a book on India during the Second World War in which

00:11:36.820 --> 00:11:40.940
[Guest]: the United States did play an important role in my research and writing.

00:11:40.940 --> 00:11:44.620
[Guest]: And it just struck me that, you know, that I actually needed to go back right to the

00:11:44.620 --> 00:11:48.740
[Guest]: moment of the founding of the American Republic, and think about US involvement with this part

00:11:48.740 --> 00:11:50.660
[Guest]: of the world in a longer term story.

00:11:50.660 --> 00:11:55.260
[Guest]: Because I think one of the great stories of the 20th century, from a historical standpoint,

00:11:55.260 --> 00:11:59.240
[Guest]: is the rise of the United States as a global power without peer and without historical

00:11:59.240 --> 00:12:02.660
[Guest]: sort of, you know, comparison being there.

00:12:02.660 --> 00:12:08.020
[Guest]: So in a sense, to me, the really interesting thing about this book was an attempt to say,

00:12:08.020 --> 00:12:11.340
[Guest]: how does South Asia fit into the story of American ascendancy?

00:12:11.340 --> 00:12:14.260
[Guest]: You know, where does this region come in, which in some ways seems so peripheral, that's

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:19.260
[Guest]: what everyone assumes, but which has from time to time, you know, imposed itself on

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:20.260
[Guest]: core concerns.

00:12:20.260 --> 00:12:23.860
[Guest]: I mean, to give you just one example, and we can pick up on other things as we go, you

00:12:23.860 --> 00:12:27.140
[Guest]: know, think of the most dangerous moment in the second half of the 20th century, the Cuban

00:12:27.140 --> 00:12:28.580
[Guest]: Missile Crisis, right?

00:12:28.580 --> 00:12:32.380
[Guest]: But the Cuban Missile Crisis is a time when the United States is so focused on its main

00:12:32.380 --> 00:12:33.940
[Guest]: rivalry with the Soviet Union, right?

00:12:33.940 --> 00:12:36.180
[Guest]: There's nuclear weapons, all of that stuff, right?

00:12:36.180 --> 00:12:39.380
[Guest]: It's everything that you would assume with the main concerns of the Cold War.

00:12:39.380 --> 00:12:43.580
[Guest]: But at the same time, the Americans are confronted with the problem that the Chinese have attacked

00:12:43.580 --> 00:12:45.060
[Guest]: India, right?

00:12:45.060 --> 00:12:47.900
[Guest]: So the Sino-Indian crisis is something that the Kennedy administration has to attend to

00:12:47.900 --> 00:12:50.780
[Guest]: even while the Cuban Missile Crisis is playing out, right?

00:12:50.780 --> 00:12:55.420
[Guest]: So in a sense, the periphery has a way of imposing itself on the core, which I think

00:12:55.420 --> 00:12:59.100
[Guest]: is the reason why history constantly surprises statesmen, right?

00:12:59.100 --> 00:13:01.100
[Guest]: Which is why somebody said, you know, a week is a long time in politics.

00:13:01.100 --> 00:13:03.460
[Guest]: I think that's the reason because you never know what's coming up next.

00:13:03.460 --> 00:13:06.620
[Amit Varma]: And your book is organized along broadly chronological lines.

00:13:06.620 --> 00:13:11.540
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, there are these three strands running through it of, you know, American

00:13:11.540 --> 00:13:17.180
[Amit Varma]: interest in South Asia, these three sort of different areas of concern for them.

00:13:17.180 --> 00:13:21.380
[Amit Varma]: So can you talk a little bit about how you made that the organizing principle in a sense?

00:13:21.380 --> 00:13:22.380
[Guest]: Yeah, sure.

00:13:22.380 --> 00:13:27.860
[Guest]: So, so the three strands that I sort of talk about really are power, ideology and culture.

00:13:27.860 --> 00:13:32.860
[Guest]: And I say that if you want to understand the sort of taken, have an interpretive grasp

00:13:32.860 --> 00:13:37.260
[Guest]: of how the United States has interacted with this part of the world and how that interaction

00:13:37.260 --> 00:13:41.740
[Guest]: has changed, has become important, less important, you know, immediate problems come in there

00:13:41.740 --> 00:13:42.740
[Guest]: are longer term.

00:13:42.740 --> 00:13:46.500
[Guest]: But from a sort of a 230 year perspective, there are these three strands which really

00:13:46.500 --> 00:13:49.820
[Guest]: stand out in American involvement with this part of the world.

00:13:49.820 --> 00:13:53.780
[Guest]: The first is power, by which I mean the pursuit of interest in the first instance of economic

00:13:53.780 --> 00:13:57.900
[Guest]: interest because that's what Americans came to the subcontinent for trade.

00:13:57.900 --> 00:14:02.580
[Guest]: But then subsequently, of course, you had geopolitical and security military interests,

00:14:02.580 --> 00:14:05.900
[Guest]: particularly in the second half of the 20th century, which becomes a very important theme.

00:14:05.900 --> 00:14:08.900
[Guest]: The second is the role of ideology.

00:14:08.900 --> 00:14:14.220
[Guest]: And there again, you know, there is a peculiar sort of American ideological constellation,

00:14:14.220 --> 00:14:17.860
[Guest]: which has been very important in the way that the United States has sort of dealt with the

00:14:17.860 --> 00:14:18.860
[Guest]: rest of the world.

00:14:18.860 --> 00:14:21.600
[Guest]: And this is something which is reasonably well established by historians of the United

00:14:21.600 --> 00:14:27.380
[Guest]: States is a combination of what you might call as Protestant and Republican ideas, right?

00:14:27.380 --> 00:14:33.420
[Guest]: So the United States has this sense of itself at the moment of its creation in 1776, as

00:14:33.420 --> 00:14:37.820
[Guest]: this divinely sort of elect country, which has a mission and that mission is the spread

00:14:37.820 --> 00:14:39.180
[Guest]: of liberty to the rest of the world, right?

00:14:39.180 --> 00:14:43.500
[Guest]: So it's a very powerful fusion of these two themes of Protestantism and Republicanism,

00:14:43.500 --> 00:14:48.860
[Guest]: which is a very peculiar feature of American sort of ideology, which again, is has been

00:14:48.860 --> 00:14:53.540
[Guest]: a running theme from the sort of moment of creation and their engagement with the subcontinent

00:14:53.540 --> 00:14:55.220
[Guest]: through almost to the present.

00:14:55.220 --> 00:14:57.820
[Guest]: I mean, you only need to think about someone like Barack Obama saying that, you know, United

00:14:57.820 --> 00:14:59.340
[Guest]: States is the indispensable nation, right?

00:14:59.340 --> 00:15:03.740
[Guest]: I mean, so there's a sense not just of exceptionalism in the ordinary sort of sense of it, but there

00:15:03.740 --> 00:15:06.300
[Guest]: is a peculiar quality to that exceptionalism.

00:15:06.300 --> 00:15:09.980
[Guest]: And I wanted to emphasize how those ideas have been very important in the way that the

00:15:09.980 --> 00:15:12.260
[Guest]: United States has dealt with this part of the world.

00:15:12.260 --> 00:15:16.780
[Guest]: And the third is really about culture, by which I actually mean two slightly different,

00:15:16.780 --> 00:15:18.820
[Guest]: but nevertheless related things.

00:15:18.820 --> 00:15:22.720
[Guest]: The first and in some ways, the easiest way is about transmission of cultural ideas, right?

00:15:22.720 --> 00:15:26.340
[Guest]: So you want to talk about things like how popular American culture, Hollywood, or in

00:15:26.340 --> 00:15:31.860
[Guest]: my case, jazz, more interestingly, has always been an important part of the way that American

00:15:31.860 --> 00:15:35.140
[Guest]: mores and values were tried to be transmitted to this part of the world.

00:15:35.140 --> 00:15:38.340
[Guest]: And of course, how people appropriate those and make very different things of them, right?

00:15:38.340 --> 00:15:42.940
[Guest]: So what does it mean to listen to, you know, Duke Ellington in Afghanistan in the early

00:15:42.940 --> 00:15:45.180
[Guest]: 1960s is an interesting question.

00:15:45.180 --> 00:15:50.700
[Guest]: I have a sort of a broader emphasis on culture, which is of saying that how do you understand

00:15:50.700 --> 00:15:54.340
[Guest]: people's societies, which are very different from you?

00:15:54.340 --> 00:15:56.860
[Guest]: How do you cope with this idea of difference?

00:15:56.860 --> 00:16:02.220
[Guest]: And there I say that, you know, American ideas of race, religion, in particular, among other

00:16:02.220 --> 00:16:05.660
[Guest]: things have been very important in the way that the United States has understood this

00:16:05.660 --> 00:16:06.660
[Guest]: about, right?

00:16:06.660 --> 00:16:11.580
[Guest]: So I use sort of accounts of missionaries, of travelers, of merchants, of people who

00:16:11.580 --> 00:16:15.460
[Guest]: are sort of engaging with this part of the world politically, journalists, and so on.

00:16:15.460 --> 00:16:21.460
[Guest]: And what do you find is that while the sort of the tenor of the engagement changes, there

00:16:21.460 --> 00:16:26.300
[Guest]: is some underlying consistency to it, which I try to capture by the idea of hierarchy,

00:16:26.300 --> 00:16:31.100
[Guest]: which is to say the Americans have always thought of the subcontinent as, you know,

00:16:31.100 --> 00:16:33.180
[Guest]: being hierarchically somewhat lower placed than them, right?

00:16:33.180 --> 00:16:35.900
[Guest]: So the Anglo-Saxons are pretty much at the top and so on.

00:16:35.900 --> 00:16:38.820
[Guest]: And, you know, these ideas tend to evolve over a period of time.

00:16:38.820 --> 00:16:42.740
[Guest]: Initially, it was about race, then it was about some sort of biological construct, then

00:16:42.740 --> 00:16:45.820
[Guest]: it's about survival of the strongest and so on.

00:16:45.820 --> 00:16:50.140
[Guest]: But right down to the 20th century, there was the sense that, you know, these are very

00:16:50.140 --> 00:16:51.140
[Guest]: different people.

00:16:51.140 --> 00:16:54.700
[Guest]: And to give you an example, I mean, even things that we wouldn't consider as sort of inflected

00:16:54.700 --> 00:16:58.300
[Guest]: with these things, like ideas about economic development in the 20th century, American

00:16:58.300 --> 00:17:02.180
[Guest]: modernization theories, which was so influential in the way that the United States assisted

00:17:02.180 --> 00:17:05.460
[Guest]: various countries with the economic development, were very much premised on this idea that

00:17:05.460 --> 00:17:08.340
[Guest]: there are some countries which are underdeveloped at the bottom of the civilizational scale,

00:17:08.340 --> 00:17:09.780
[Guest]: and others are at the top.

00:17:09.780 --> 00:17:13.260
[Guest]: And the challenge is to get those at the bottom to emulate those at the top.

00:17:13.260 --> 00:17:18.060
[Guest]: So in that sense, I say that, you know, this notion of hierarchy has been remarkably sort

00:17:18.060 --> 00:17:22.380
[Guest]: of durable, and is a very important part of understanding how the Americans understood.

00:17:22.380 --> 00:17:26.500
[Guest]: Because in some ways, when we think about things like interests, or power, you know,

00:17:26.500 --> 00:17:28.180
[Guest]: we almost think of them as tangible things, right?

00:17:28.180 --> 00:17:30.900
[Guest]: I mean, that's why everyone says, you know, you've got to be realistic, because you think

00:17:30.900 --> 00:17:33.060
[Guest]: that politics is about power and so on.

00:17:33.060 --> 00:17:36.020
[Guest]: But power is something that is ultimately about how you perceive it, right?

00:17:36.020 --> 00:17:39.660
[Guest]: So how your interests get constituted in the first place, I think, is a very important

00:17:39.660 --> 00:17:42.100
[Guest]: part of understanding any political process.

00:17:42.100 --> 00:17:44.980
[Guest]: And there, this cultural dimension of it seems to me to be very, very important.

00:17:44.980 --> 00:17:49.140
[Guest]: I mean, the way that the Americans from very early on made a distinction between Islam

00:17:49.140 --> 00:17:52.500
[Guest]: and Hinduism in the subcontinent, you know, those had sort of implications for the way

00:17:52.500 --> 00:17:54.420
[Guest]: they saw India and Pakistan after 1947.

00:17:54.420 --> 00:17:55.420
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:17:55.420 --> 00:17:59.460
[Amit Varma]: And you sort of start off the book talking about the late 18th century traders who first

00:17:59.460 --> 00:18:03.100
[Amit Varma]: came here, and immediately you see a confluence of both the economic interests, because they've

00:18:03.100 --> 00:18:07.780
[Amit Varma]: obviously come to make money and also this cultural aspect that you speak of where that

00:18:07.780 --> 00:18:11.700
[Amit Varma]: sense of racial and cultural superiority is immediately evident.

00:18:11.700 --> 00:18:16.940
[Amit Varma]: And it almost seems to arise to begin with from a visceral reaction to sort of what they

00:18:16.940 --> 00:18:17.940
[Amit Varma]: saw around them.

00:18:17.940 --> 00:18:21.980
[Amit Varma]: Like there's one writer you've quoted in your book who talks about being so disgusted by

00:18:21.980 --> 00:18:25.700
[Amit Varma]: a quote unquote, loathsome beggar, that he can't even get himself to hit him because

00:18:25.700 --> 00:18:30.020
[Amit Varma]: he can't even you know, and and that sense of, you know, so they have this condescending

00:18:30.020 --> 00:18:36.420
[Amit Varma]: and very superior attitude towards Indians aligned with this, you know, or rather sort

00:18:36.420 --> 00:18:42.020
[Amit Varma]: of contrasted with their economic interest in, you know, embedding themselves and kind

00:18:42.020 --> 00:18:43.020
[Guest]: of making money.

00:18:43.020 --> 00:18:44.020
[Guest]: That is right.

00:18:44.020 --> 00:18:48.260
[Guest]: Because, you know, the one thing we have to realize is that in the early decades after

00:18:48.260 --> 00:18:53.100
[Guest]: American independence in 1776, see, the United States was in pretty much in doldrums economically,

00:18:53.100 --> 00:18:54.100
[Guest]: right.

00:18:54.100 --> 00:18:58.540
[Guest]: And there was a huge outward drive towards finding new markets, new avenues for trade

00:18:58.540 --> 00:18:59.620
[Guest]: and so on.

00:18:59.620 --> 00:19:03.580
[Guest]: And there was a very influential group of, you know, merchant seafaring merchants based

00:19:03.580 --> 00:19:09.420
[Guest]: primarily in the Boston area, New England, who became the vanguard of much of this trade.

00:19:09.420 --> 00:19:11.180
[Guest]: China was always a very important destination.

00:19:11.180 --> 00:19:14.820
[Guest]: But in the course of that, India also becomes quite important.

00:19:14.820 --> 00:19:19.340
[Guest]: And tracing those links is one of the sort of major challenges of seeing how the early

00:19:19.340 --> 00:19:20.500
[Guest]: interactions happened.

00:19:20.500 --> 00:19:25.220
[Guest]: But as you're saying, even economic sort of interactions are influenced, inflected through

00:19:25.220 --> 00:19:27.940
[Guest]: this cultural prism through which the Americans are trying to perceive.

00:19:27.940 --> 00:19:31.180
[Guest]: And I don't want to give a sense that, you know, this is some kind of simple monolithic

00:19:31.180 --> 00:19:33.980
[Guest]: idea of sort of superiority out there.

00:19:33.980 --> 00:19:39.540
[Guest]: I think the fundamental issue is not so much about superiority, inferiority as about some

00:19:39.540 --> 00:19:43.380
[Guest]: sense of hierarchy, which is to say that even if people are at the bottom, you feel that,

00:19:43.380 --> 00:19:44.380
[Guest]: you know, they need to be helped, right?

00:19:44.380 --> 00:19:48.200
[Guest]: I mean, so even a benevolent impulse can come from a sense of hierarchy.

00:19:48.200 --> 00:19:50.940
[Guest]: And at bottom, this is about how you deal with difference.

00:19:50.940 --> 00:19:52.780
[Guest]: How do you deal with people who are so different from you are, right?

00:19:52.780 --> 00:19:56.260
[Guest]: How do you deal with a religion like Hinduism or whatever, a group of people who call themselves

00:19:56.260 --> 00:20:01.460
[Guest]: the Hindus, who have this unique institution called the caste system, you know, which you've

00:20:01.460 --> 00:20:02.460
[Guest]: never sort of come across.

00:20:02.460 --> 00:20:05.940
[Guest]: I mean, you have race in America, which is very understandable to you.

00:20:05.940 --> 00:20:09.980
[Guest]: But then you use the prism of the race to understand how this sort of caste arrangement

00:20:09.980 --> 00:20:11.300
[Guest]: works here, right?

00:20:11.300 --> 00:20:13.220
[Guest]: And then you come up with certain kinds of...

00:20:13.220 --> 00:20:19.620
[Guest]: So those ideas, the sort of often contradictory impulses and constellation of things crystallize

00:20:19.620 --> 00:20:20.940
[Guest]: over a period of time.

00:20:20.940 --> 00:20:27.180
[Guest]: And what I then try and show is how they remain durable and important well into the 20th century.

00:20:27.180 --> 00:20:30.780
[Amit Varma]: And what you really have in the first half of the 19th century, as you describe it, is

00:20:30.780 --> 00:20:36.260
[Amit Varma]: that American interaction with South Asia, with India and so on is basically takes two

00:20:36.260 --> 00:20:37.260
[Amit Varma]: manifestations.

00:20:37.260 --> 00:20:38.980
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one is trade, one is missionaries.

00:20:38.980 --> 00:20:42.420
[Amit Varma]: So the missionaries, of course, embodying what you call the benevolent impulse that

00:20:42.420 --> 00:20:45.620
[Amit Varma]: these are low people and we must lift them up.

00:20:45.620 --> 00:20:47.400
[Amit Varma]: And trade, of course, being what it is.

00:20:47.400 --> 00:20:52.140
[Amit Varma]: And gradually during this time, you talk about how India for them evolves from being a quote

00:20:52.140 --> 00:20:54.860
[Amit Varma]: unquote land of fortune to a realm of fantasy.

00:20:54.860 --> 00:21:00.580
[Amit Varma]: And you know, where they get more interested in sort of the spiritual aspect of India,

00:21:00.580 --> 00:21:05.060
[Amit Varma]: you know, the transcendentalists sort of also get pretty influenced by that.

00:21:05.060 --> 00:21:09.820
[Amit Varma]: But in the middle of the 19th century, you point to two things, two events, which change

00:21:09.820 --> 00:21:13.180
[Amit Varma]: that interaction between America and South Asia completely.

00:21:13.180 --> 00:21:14.180
[Guest]: That's right.

00:21:14.180 --> 00:21:19.060
[Guest]: So the two events that you're referring to are the sort of Indian sort of rebellion of

00:21:19.060 --> 00:21:24.820
[Guest]: 1857-58 and the American Civil War, which starts just a few years afterwards.

00:21:24.820 --> 00:21:30.420
[Guest]: And both of these are sort of important historical ruptures in these societies in their own right.

00:21:30.420 --> 00:21:34.220
[Guest]: But what it means is that the early period of interaction, when you have this very dense

00:21:34.220 --> 00:21:37.380
[Guest]: commercial exchanges, all of that comes to a close, right?

00:21:37.380 --> 00:21:39.900
[Guest]: Now, in some ways, India does benefit from the American Civil War.

00:21:39.900 --> 00:21:43.260
[Guest]: For instance, Indian cotton exports had a huge boom because American sort of cotton

00:21:43.260 --> 00:21:45.460
[Guest]: was sort of locked up, right, because of the Civil War and so on.

00:21:45.460 --> 00:21:49.660
[Guest]: So you did have some or even things like, you know, the export of sort of Pashmina from

00:21:49.660 --> 00:21:50.660
[Guest]: Kashmir.

00:21:50.660 --> 00:21:53.440
[Guest]: Kashmir actually experienced a major boom during the American Civil War.

00:21:53.440 --> 00:21:54.980
[Guest]: So you did have some benefits.

00:21:54.980 --> 00:21:59.700
[Guest]: But the reality was that the, you know, the sort of the long distance trade, which was

00:21:59.700 --> 00:22:03.540
[Guest]: a mainstay in some ways, comes to an end because of this period.

00:22:03.540 --> 00:22:07.740
[Guest]: And after that, when there is a reconfiguration, it happens in more or less autonomous ways,

00:22:07.740 --> 00:22:08.740
[Guest]: right?

00:22:08.740 --> 00:22:13.080
[Guest]: So after the Indian sort of rebellion is quelled and India is integrated in the British Empire,

00:22:13.080 --> 00:22:16.620
[Guest]: you have the integration of India with the global economy under the aegis of the British

00:22:16.620 --> 00:22:17.620
[Guest]: Empire, right?

00:22:17.620 --> 00:22:20.960
[Guest]: So that's a very different form of engagement with the rest of the world.

00:22:20.960 --> 00:22:24.260
[Guest]: And the United States, of course, becomes this continent sized economy at home, which

00:22:24.260 --> 00:22:28.420
[Guest]: Americans realize that, you know, if only we know how to exploit this market, then we

00:22:28.420 --> 00:22:32.860
[Guest]: are set because, you know, and for the rest of the 19th century and well into the 20th

00:22:32.860 --> 00:22:36.260
[Guest]: century, the rest of the world actually matters very little in terms of trade for the United

00:22:36.260 --> 00:22:37.260
[Guest]: States.

00:22:37.260 --> 00:22:40.020
[Guest]: I mean, even today, actually, if you just look at traders percentage of American GDP,

00:22:40.020 --> 00:22:43.900
[Guest]: you will find that it's much lesser than that of any other advanced economy, because the

00:22:43.900 --> 00:22:48.740
[Guest]: United States has this humongous advantage of a continent sized economy, which the Americans

00:22:48.740 --> 00:22:53.660
[Guest]: were learning to sort of integrate, exploit, build companies on scale, etc, etc.

00:22:53.660 --> 00:22:54.980
[Guest]: All of that happens in the 19th century.

00:22:54.980 --> 00:23:00.900
[Guest]: So that the two sort of revolutions are in some ways, a major point of rupture.

00:23:00.900 --> 00:23:04.500
[Guest]: But nevertheless, there are some continuities across this period, particularly in the realm

00:23:04.500 --> 00:23:07.380
[Guest]: of some of those things you mentioned, like the activities of missionaries, right?

00:23:07.380 --> 00:23:13.740
[Guest]: And again, I think the whole question of missionaries and religion shows the kind of contradictory

00:23:13.740 --> 00:23:15.220
[Guest]: strands that you had to this interaction.

00:23:15.220 --> 00:23:17.260
[Guest]: Once again, it's not monolithic at all.

00:23:17.260 --> 00:23:21.020
[Guest]: So on the one hand, you had these missionaries who first came to the subcontinent in 1812.

00:23:21.020 --> 00:23:25.420
[Guest]: Now before that period, the British East India Company would not allow any missionary activity

00:23:25.420 --> 00:23:27.820
[Guest]: to happen in India, including British missionaries were not allowed.

00:23:27.820 --> 00:23:31.220
[Guest]: So when it opens up, that's the time when the Americans are also constituting the missionary

00:23:31.220 --> 00:23:32.220
[Guest]: board.

00:23:32.220 --> 00:23:33.960
[Guest]: So it's a good, nice confluence of things.

00:23:33.960 --> 00:23:37.860
[Guest]: So American missionaries start coming to this part of the world, you know, as early as 1813,

00:23:37.860 --> 00:23:41.940
[Guest]: they are in Burma in places of what you'd call like Nagaland today already.

00:23:41.940 --> 00:23:44.180
[Guest]: But then they spread out to other parts of the world.

00:23:44.180 --> 00:23:48.020
[Guest]: And you know, initially, they have very little success in their actual mission, which is

00:23:48.020 --> 00:23:51.300
[Guest]: that of harvesting souls and converting people to Christianity.

00:23:51.300 --> 00:23:55.020
[Guest]: But there are other kinds of social sort of consequences which follow from missionary

00:23:55.020 --> 00:23:58.940
[Guest]: activity are I think very important, and are running through the 19th century into the

00:23:58.940 --> 00:23:59.940
[Guest]: early 20th century.

00:23:59.940 --> 00:24:04.420
[Guest]: You know, the missionaries are the first ones who introduced print culture in various parts

00:24:04.420 --> 00:24:07.340
[Guest]: of India, including Western India, you know, we're doing this in Bombay.

00:24:07.340 --> 00:24:11.300
[Guest]: And, you know, this part of the world benefited a lot from various kinds of printing presses

00:24:11.300 --> 00:24:12.980
[Guest]: established by the missionaries.

00:24:12.980 --> 00:24:16.740
[Guest]: The missionaries were the first ones actually to have, you know, dictionaries for Indian

00:24:16.740 --> 00:24:20.300
[Guest]: languages in English, because they had to sort of translate the Bible, because you know,

00:24:20.300 --> 00:24:22.940
[Guest]: Protestantism expects that you would engage with the text yourself, right?

00:24:22.940 --> 00:24:27.220
[Guest]: They were the first ones who emphasized primary education, even for women and girls.

00:24:27.220 --> 00:24:32.140
[Guest]: Jyoti Bapule and his wife were both, you know, educated in missionary schools.

00:24:32.140 --> 00:24:35.900
[Guest]: You know, the missionaries in Southern India, like my home state of Tamil Nadu, were very

00:24:35.900 --> 00:24:40.260
[Guest]: active in what were then known as the paraya colonies or where Dalits lived and, you know,

00:24:40.260 --> 00:24:44.660
[Guest]: very influential in giving them education, allowing them, sensitizing them to land rights

00:24:44.660 --> 00:24:45.660
[Guest]: and such like things.

00:24:45.660 --> 00:24:51.260
[Guest]: You know, later in the 19th century, missionaries were active in famine relief in Victorian

00:24:51.260 --> 00:24:52.260
[Guest]: India.

00:24:52.260 --> 00:24:57.220
[Guest]: And of course, you know, they were active in a range of sort of quasi developmental medical

00:24:57.220 --> 00:24:58.220
[Guest]: activities as well.

00:24:58.220 --> 00:25:00.740
[Guest]: You know, you think of something like Christian Missionary College in Vellore, which is the

00:25:00.740 --> 00:25:04.980
[Guest]: first big medical college in this country set up by American missionaries.

00:25:04.980 --> 00:25:07.860
[Guest]: You know, the eradication of hookworm was actually undertaken by American missionaries

00:25:07.860 --> 00:25:12.020
[Guest]: supported by the Rockefeller Foundation already by 1910-15.

00:25:12.020 --> 00:25:15.420
[Guest]: So you have this extraordinary seam of activity, which is continuing despite this rupture.

00:25:15.420 --> 00:25:19.940
[Amit Varma]: And would you say this is something that is part of or runs parallel to America's otherwise

00:25:19.940 --> 00:25:24.100
[Amit Varma]: sense of manifest destiny, you know, which, you know, you've defined as, you know, the

00:25:24.100 --> 00:25:26.780
[Amit Varma]: spread of liberty and republicanism and all that.

00:25:26.780 --> 00:25:31.260
[Amit Varma]: But it seems that at another level, there is, and this perhaps arises to begin with

00:25:31.260 --> 00:25:36.020
[Amit Varma]: out of the benevolent instinct, but is also, you know, a sort of a reform process at the

00:25:36.020 --> 00:25:39.580
[Amit Varma]: same time where they see all these things that are wrong with the local culture in their

00:25:39.580 --> 00:25:41.700
[Amit Varma]: eyes, of course, not necessarily otherwise.

00:25:41.700 --> 00:25:44.060
[Amit Varma]: And then they try to reform it and a lot of good comes out of that.

00:25:44.060 --> 00:25:46.860
[Guest]: No, I think it's very much part of this process, right.

00:25:46.860 --> 00:25:51.940
[Guest]: So the idea of manifest destiny is first, you know, adumbrated in the American context

00:25:51.940 --> 00:25:53.700
[Guest]: in the 1830s.

00:25:53.700 --> 00:25:57.660
[Guest]: And the idea is to say that, you know, basically United States has is destined to conquer all

00:25:57.660 --> 00:26:00.960
[Guest]: of North America, right, because there were all these territories which were occupied

00:26:00.960 --> 00:26:06.100
[Guest]: by indigenous communities, the Indians in North America, and manifest destiny was basically

00:26:06.100 --> 00:26:11.620
[Guest]: an ideological sort of justification for American expansion in a continental sense, right.

00:26:11.620 --> 00:26:15.740
[Guest]: But what is interesting, and to me, it was very striking was how this whole ideology

00:26:15.740 --> 00:26:21.180
[Guest]: of manifest destiny in some ways was always justified as being completely in contrast

00:26:21.180 --> 00:26:25.580
[Guest]: to the imperialism being practiced by other countries like Britain, particularly in cases

00:26:25.580 --> 00:26:26.580
[Guest]: like India, right.

00:26:26.580 --> 00:26:32.740
[Guest]: So, American imperialism at home, or American expansionism at home, was always seen as a

00:26:32.740 --> 00:26:36.680
[Guest]: better alternative to the kind of exploitation of countries like India that were being done

00:26:36.680 --> 00:26:37.680
[Guest]: by the British, right.

00:26:37.680 --> 00:26:38.680
[Amit Varma]: In the sense of less coercive.

00:26:38.680 --> 00:26:41.820
[Guest]: Yeah, not just less coercive, but they believe that, you know, Americans are settlers, they

00:26:41.820 --> 00:26:44.980
[Guest]: actually settle down in this land, whereas British are just coming, they're visiting,

00:26:44.980 --> 00:26:47.780
[Guest]: they're going back, they're exploiting this country, they're taking away its treasures.

00:26:47.780 --> 00:26:53.940
[Guest]: So it's very interesting how the American reading of India up to the mid 19th century

00:26:53.940 --> 00:26:58.060
[Guest]: is really, you know, is a mirror through which they look at Britain itself, right, which

00:26:58.060 --> 00:27:00.420
[Guest]: is a country with which they have very serious problems at this point of time.

00:27:00.420 --> 00:27:04.020
[Amit Varma]: In fact, in one of your early chapters, you've also cited this defense of slavery that was

00:27:04.020 --> 00:27:07.560
[Amit Varma]: made by someone who said that, hey, you talk about slavery, but look at the British oppression

00:27:07.560 --> 00:27:09.580
[Guest]: of the Indian natives that is far, far worse.

00:27:09.580 --> 00:27:10.580
[Guest]: Exactly, right.

00:27:10.580 --> 00:27:14.660
[Guest]: And in a sense, once Britain becomes this great advocate of abolition of slavery, you

00:27:14.660 --> 00:27:17.900
[Guest]: know, that the whole abolitionist movement is in Britain, the Americans, especially in

00:27:17.900 --> 00:27:22.260
[Guest]: the South, who are the pro slavery lot, are, you know, constantly calling out British hypocrisy

00:27:22.260 --> 00:27:23.260
[Guest]: by pointing to India, right.

00:27:23.260 --> 00:27:26.080
[Guest]: So in a sense, India is part of those domestic American debates.

00:27:26.080 --> 00:27:29.020
[Guest]: So it's in that sense that I feel that, you know, while in a sense, many people may not

00:27:29.020 --> 00:27:33.940
[Guest]: have actually known India, India did have an important part in this American ideology.

00:27:33.940 --> 00:27:37.260
[Guest]: And of course, Protestantism and the role of the missions was very much part of this

00:27:37.260 --> 00:27:42.140
[Guest]: idea that, you know, the United States has discovered this unique constellation of providential

00:27:42.140 --> 00:27:47.860
[Guest]: sort of, you know, faith based sort of blessings with this ability to sort of craft a republican

00:27:47.860 --> 00:27:51.940
[Guest]: model of politics and that this is in some ways the best thing for the rest of the world,

00:27:51.940 --> 00:27:52.940
[Guest]: right.

00:27:52.940 --> 00:27:55.260
[Guest]: And of course, there were differences even the United States about how to take that in

00:27:55.260 --> 00:28:00.340
[Guest]: some ways mirrors this whole democracy promotion kind of debates of the last decade, you know,

00:28:00.340 --> 00:28:05.340
[Guest]: which is to say that should the United States sort of, you know, stand as a shining city

00:28:05.340 --> 00:28:09.220
[Guest]: on the hill and act as a model or should it actually be sort of doing things actively

00:28:09.220 --> 00:28:10.220
[Guest]: and so on.

00:28:10.220 --> 00:28:12.060
[Guest]: And then there were always debates about those kinds of things.

00:28:12.060 --> 00:28:16.460
[Guest]: But I think there was a broad consensus that yes, the United States was in some ways destined

00:28:16.460 --> 00:28:21.060
[Guest]: and they were people who were chosen, elect, which is a Protestant sort of way of thinking.

00:28:21.060 --> 00:28:23.900
[Amit Varma]: And I guess if there was an ebb and flow on this, you could say the period between the

00:28:23.900 --> 00:28:28.500
[Amit Varma]: two world wars was sort of the ebb when it, you know, drifted more towards isolationism

00:28:28.500 --> 00:28:30.380
[Amit Varma]: and saying, hey, we'll have nothing to do with the world.

00:28:30.380 --> 00:28:33.500
[Amit Varma]: And that's also a very interesting period in world history, because for the first time,

00:28:33.500 --> 00:28:36.300
[Amit Varma]: you don't really have one dominant power anymore.

00:28:36.300 --> 00:28:40.420
[Amit Varma]: You know, Britain has kind of lost some of that and there's sort of a vacuum within which

00:28:40.420 --> 00:28:44.940
[Amit Varma]: the Great Depression happens and Nazi Germany happens and all those kind of things happen.

00:28:44.940 --> 00:28:49.700
[Amit Varma]: So but in that period, what I also found interesting in your book is that you see, you know, you've

00:28:49.700 --> 00:28:54.220
[Amit Varma]: pointed out the various contradictory stands of one, there is this growing cultural fascination

00:28:54.220 --> 00:28:59.300
[Amit Varma]: with India, especially someone like Gandhi, who was described by them as the greatest

00:28:59.300 --> 00:29:02.860
[Amit Varma]: living person and Time magazine made him person of the year in 1930.

00:29:02.860 --> 00:29:05.820
[Amit Varma]: And there's something symbiotic there also, because a lot of Gandhi's inspiration came

00:29:05.820 --> 00:29:09.700
[Amit Varma]: from Thoreau and a lot of Thoreau's inspirations came from Indian mysticism.

00:29:09.700 --> 00:29:11.260
[Amit Varma]: So it's kind of funny that way.

00:29:11.260 --> 00:29:15.700
[Amit Varma]: But that again, is in contrast to this anti immigration sentiment that is coming up and

00:29:15.700 --> 00:29:19.420
[Amit Varma]: the trouble that Indian immigrants in America are facing.

00:29:19.420 --> 00:29:23.380
[Amit Varma]: But broadly, by the time the World War Two happens, you pointed to a couple of public

00:29:23.380 --> 00:29:27.940
[Amit Varma]: polls, where there is widespread support for Indian independence in America, even though

00:29:27.940 --> 00:29:31.820
[Amit Varma]: America, the state itself has taken a step back and saying, hey, you know, we're not

00:29:31.820 --> 00:29:33.460
[Amit Varma]: going to interfere with the rest of the world.

00:29:33.460 --> 00:29:34.460
[Guest]: That's right.

00:29:34.460 --> 00:29:38.420
[Guest]: I think the period between the two world wars is kind of interesting, because while the

00:29:38.420 --> 00:29:43.060
[Guest]: United States is not directly politically engaged, there is a much growing, greater

00:29:43.060 --> 00:29:46.460
[Guest]: awareness of Indian politics, Indian society and so on.

00:29:46.460 --> 00:29:50.260
[Guest]: And you know, this whole fascination with Gandhi in some ways is a reaction to the First

00:29:50.260 --> 00:29:51.260
[Guest]: World War, right?

00:29:51.260 --> 00:29:54.580
[Guest]: Because after the end of the war, you know, there's a huge pacifist movement, which happens

00:29:54.580 --> 00:29:58.580
[Guest]: in most Western countries, to which there is a strand, even in the United States, and

00:29:58.580 --> 00:30:02.300
[Guest]: some of the, you know, better known figures of that period, you know, actually came out

00:30:02.300 --> 00:30:05.540
[Guest]: of that strand of pacifist thinking.

00:30:05.540 --> 00:30:10.380
[Guest]: And for them, you know, Gandhi was this sort of scene as embodying this new form of politics,

00:30:10.380 --> 00:30:13.500
[Guest]: which emphasizes nonviolence and civil disobedience.

00:30:13.500 --> 00:30:19.060
[Guest]: And as you say, you know, in some ways, that goes back to Thoreau, whom Gandhi had read.

00:30:19.060 --> 00:30:24.460
[Guest]: Now, you know, in an earlier question, you'd asked about, you know, this sort of transcendentalists

00:30:24.460 --> 00:30:28.780
[Guest]: who are a group of, again, intellectuals, mostly in and around Boston, who are very

00:30:28.780 --> 00:30:34.100
[Guest]: fascinated by India in the mid 19th century, Emerson, Thoreau, and others.

00:30:34.100 --> 00:30:37.620
[Guest]: The interesting thing is how this phenomenon is a constant recurrence, right?

00:30:37.620 --> 00:30:42.140
[Guest]: So, you have the transcendentalists in the mid 19th century, you have the American pacifists

00:30:42.140 --> 00:30:43.940
[Guest]: in the early 20th century.

00:30:43.940 --> 00:30:46.820
[Guest]: And if you fast forward into the 1960s, you have the American sort of hippie trail, so

00:30:46.820 --> 00:30:47.820
[Guest]: to speak, right?

00:30:47.820 --> 00:30:53.220
[Guest]: Now, in each of these instances, what you find is that India and its culture, particularly

00:30:53.220 --> 00:30:56.740
[Guest]: the Indian sort of religion, especially the high philosophical sort of, you know, the

00:30:56.740 --> 00:31:02.720
[Guest]: Upanishads and the mysticism, the sort of the metaphysics, so to speak, is seen as providing

00:31:02.720 --> 00:31:06.980
[Guest]: an antidote to American commercialism, to American militarism, you know, in a sense,

00:31:06.980 --> 00:31:08.980
[Guest]: India is this other to the United States, right?

00:31:08.980 --> 00:31:10.940
[Guest]: So there's this constant fascination.

00:31:10.940 --> 00:31:15.300
[Guest]: So with India as somehow providing a refute from everything that is wrong with the United

00:31:15.300 --> 00:31:16.300
[Guest]: States, right?

00:31:16.300 --> 00:31:18.300
[Guest]: So in a sense, the Gandhian moment is very much like that.

00:31:18.300 --> 00:31:22.340
[Guest]: But what you find is that in the 1920s and 30s, there are lots of Americans who come,

00:31:22.340 --> 00:31:23.900
[Guest]: who spend a lot of time with Gandhi.

00:31:23.900 --> 00:31:29.380
[Guest]: In fact, some of the first expositions in sort of outside of India of Gandhian nonviolence

00:31:29.380 --> 00:31:32.420
[Guest]: and its principles were undertaken by people.

00:31:32.420 --> 00:31:36.300
[Guest]: Now these people, of course, went back and influenced another generation of American

00:31:36.300 --> 00:31:39.940
[Guest]: activists during the civil rights movement, who again looked to Gandhi, you know, Martin

00:31:39.940 --> 00:31:43.820
[Guest]: Luther King and others, for whom this was very important.

00:31:43.820 --> 00:31:47.660
[Guest]: And of course, you know, and then vice versa, as you're saying that the transmission belt

00:31:47.660 --> 00:31:53.300
[Guest]: of this kind of interaction between particularly groups of African Americans and the Indian

00:31:53.300 --> 00:31:54.820
[Guest]: nationalist movement was very strong, right?

00:31:54.820 --> 00:31:59.580
[Guest]: So you have a figure like Kamala Devi Chattopadhyay, who goes to the United States and, you know,

00:31:59.580 --> 00:32:04.420
[Guest]: and then this sort of is really very well received in terms of the kinds of audiences

00:32:04.420 --> 00:32:08.260
[Guest]: that she has and understands and tries to relate these two problems, right?

00:32:08.260 --> 00:32:12.340
[Guest]: So there is a sense that just as African Americans are being oppressed within the United States

00:32:12.340 --> 00:32:16.540
[Guest]: of America, the, you know, there is a problem of imperialism, which is seen as a sort of

00:32:16.540 --> 00:32:18.580
[Guest]: international counterpart to a domestic problem, right?

00:32:18.580 --> 00:32:22.300
[Guest]: So there are these many ways in which India and the United States at a sort of a common

00:32:22.300 --> 00:32:28.420
[Guest]: popular level of that of the people come together before this great sort of geopolitical, you

00:32:28.420 --> 00:32:31.380
[Guest]: know, watershed of the Second World War happens.

00:32:31.380 --> 00:32:35.380
[Amit Varma]: And then with the Second World War, obviously, the US has to shed its isolationism.

00:32:35.380 --> 00:32:39.580
[Amit Varma]: And you also have, you know, you also write about how Roosevelt is favorably inclined

00:32:39.580 --> 00:32:43.180
[Amit Varma]: towards Indian independence, he pushes the cause, he tries to intervene, for example,

00:32:43.180 --> 00:32:47.300
[Amit Varma]: when there is a famine in Bengal, and at various times, he tries to intervene with Churchill

00:32:47.300 --> 00:32:50.480
[Amit Varma]: to sort of take a kinder attitude.

00:32:50.480 --> 00:32:55.600
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, there is a fact that India is, you know, also part of the war and

00:32:55.600 --> 00:32:57.180
[Amit Varma]: Japan can invade at any time.

00:32:57.180 --> 00:33:00.180
[Amit Varma]: So giving them independence now makes no sense.

00:33:00.180 --> 00:33:06.220
[Amit Varma]: And you know, so Roosevelt also has to kind of contend with those sort of how did all

00:33:06.220 --> 00:33:07.220
[Guest]: of that play out?

00:33:07.220 --> 00:33:12.380
[Guest]: So, you know, by the time the Second World War begins, September 1939, the story in India

00:33:12.380 --> 00:33:17.740
[Guest]: is that, you know, India has basically taken into the war, without any consultation with

00:33:17.740 --> 00:33:21.340
[Guest]: any Indian, you know, sort of political groups.

00:33:21.340 --> 00:33:24.740
[Guest]: It's worth recalling that at this point of time, it was Indian political parties, which

00:33:24.740 --> 00:33:28.580
[Guest]: were in power in the provinces, Congress Party, of course, but others as well.

00:33:28.580 --> 00:33:32.220
[Guest]: And that, you know, the Congress actually decides not to support the war effort, even

00:33:32.220 --> 00:33:35.020
[Guest]: though they are favorably sort of, they do believe that the fascists have to be sort

00:33:35.020 --> 00:33:36.800
[Guest]: of Nazis have to be resisted.

00:33:36.800 --> 00:33:40.500
[Guest]: But they believe that Britain cannot on the one hand say that it's fighting for democracy

00:33:40.500 --> 00:33:42.700
[Guest]: while withholding rights of Indians.

00:33:42.700 --> 00:33:47.460
[Guest]: So there is this period of impasse, really between 1939 and 1942, when the Congress Party

00:33:47.460 --> 00:33:52.540
[Guest]: is kind of trying to toy with various kinds of positions, which will allow it to reconcile

00:33:52.540 --> 00:33:55.860
[Guest]: both these imperatives, one of supporting the war effort, which at least people like

00:33:55.860 --> 00:33:59.340
[Guest]: Varlalai Roo and most of the other leadership was very favorably inclined.

00:33:59.340 --> 00:34:03.740
[Guest]: Gandhi, of course, had a very different view because of his sort of stance on nonviolence.

00:34:03.740 --> 00:34:08.300
[Guest]: But at the same time, you know, you also want some kind of statement from the British about

00:34:08.300 --> 00:34:10.820
[Guest]: independence for India, which is not forthcoming at all.

00:34:10.820 --> 00:34:15.100
[Guest]: And the United States has been sort of watching this and once the attack on Pearl Harbor,

00:34:15.100 --> 00:34:19.900
[Guest]: which coincides with attacks on various British territories of Southeast Asia, and the advance

00:34:19.900 --> 00:34:26.300
[Guest]: of Japanese to Burma by March, April 1942 happens and the United States is fully engaged,

00:34:26.300 --> 00:34:30.820
[Guest]: then they decide that, you know, India has to be sort of bought into the war effort wholeheartedly

00:34:30.820 --> 00:34:34.480
[Guest]: rather than this kind of a situation where their cooperation at the popular level seems

00:34:34.480 --> 00:34:37.860
[Guest]: to be withheld, even though the Indian army is growing pretty fast.

00:34:37.860 --> 00:34:41.900
[Guest]: But so it's in that context of the Roosevelt administration, actually, President Roosevelt

00:34:41.900 --> 00:34:46.180
[Guest]: himself leans on Churchill to say that, you know, you have to sort of give some attention

00:34:46.180 --> 00:34:47.180
[Guest]: to the India problem.

00:34:47.180 --> 00:34:51.940
[Guest]: And it is against that backdrop that the famous sort of mission led by Stafford Cripps comes

00:34:51.940 --> 00:34:56.820
[Guest]: to India to discuss with Indian leaders of various kinds about what kind of a constitutional

00:34:56.820 --> 00:35:00.740
[Guest]: settlement can come up for India and with what timetable and so on.

00:35:00.740 --> 00:35:02.000
[Guest]: Now the mission fails.

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:06.660
[Guest]: But what is interesting is how interested the Americans are in keeping that going.

00:35:06.660 --> 00:35:09.900
[Guest]: Now even after that failure, the Americans don't disengage immediately.

00:35:09.900 --> 00:35:13.820
[Guest]: It's actually the turning point really comes with the Quit India movement, which was a

00:35:13.820 --> 00:35:17.980
[Guest]: popular movement, even though we tend to associate it with Gandhi and others, you know, what

00:35:17.980 --> 00:35:21.260
[Guest]: a Karo Yamaro kind of slogan and so on, you know, do or die.

00:35:21.260 --> 00:35:25.300
[Guest]: But the reality was that a lot of people started doing things quite autonomously during the

00:35:25.300 --> 00:35:26.300
[Guest]: Quit India movement, right?

00:35:26.300 --> 00:35:30.620
[Guest]: So there were many groups of protesters who went, the Quit India movement was quite violent.

00:35:30.620 --> 00:35:35.260
[Guest]: You know, at least in eastern India and Bengal and other parts, there were military supply

00:35:35.260 --> 00:35:39.300
[Guest]: lines which were being sort of endangered by the activities of the rebels.

00:35:39.300 --> 00:35:41.980
[Guest]: And it is in that context that the Americans actually decide that we have to prioritize

00:35:41.980 --> 00:35:45.020
[Guest]: the war with Japan over a domestic Indian political settlement.

00:35:45.020 --> 00:35:49.020
[Guest]: And we cannot jeopardize this at this point of time by choosing sides between.

00:35:49.020 --> 00:35:52.940
[Guest]: And of course, Churchill is an important ally because they do want Britain to remain engaged

00:35:52.940 --> 00:35:53.940
[Guest]: in the war.

00:35:53.940 --> 00:35:59.260
[Guest]: So in that context, Americans sort of take a back step and then don't really try and

00:35:59.260 --> 00:36:01.140
[Guest]: play much of a role.

00:36:01.140 --> 00:36:05.140
[Guest]: Though it's quite interesting that, you know, even successive sort of emissaries sent by

00:36:05.140 --> 00:36:11.300
[Guest]: Roosevelt, however, tend to take a very sympathetic line towards, you know, Indian nationalism,

00:36:11.300 --> 00:36:14.780
[Guest]: towards the Congress Party, towards Gandhi, who was in a major fast in early 1943.

00:36:14.780 --> 00:36:16.940
[Amit Varma]: At one point, it looks like he might just die.

00:36:16.940 --> 00:36:19.140
[Amit Varma]: And the Americans are intervening saying save his life.

00:36:19.140 --> 00:36:20.140
[Guest]: Yeah, right.

00:36:20.140 --> 00:36:21.140
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:36:21.140 --> 00:36:22.860
[Guest]: So, so in a sense, there is a degree of this thing.

00:36:22.860 --> 00:36:27.820
[Guest]: But India becomes very important from the perspective of the war, because by 1943, India

00:36:27.820 --> 00:36:32.460
[Guest]: emerges as this most important allied base for operations in Southeast Asia.

00:36:32.460 --> 00:36:37.300
[Guest]: The Americans are involved in the subcontinent directly, in a sense of supporting economic

00:36:37.300 --> 00:36:43.140
[Guest]: sort of activity around the war, the war effort itself, you know, it's striking.

00:36:43.140 --> 00:36:47.740
[Guest]: There's one part of the rail network between Calcutta and Assam, which was then, you know,

00:36:47.740 --> 00:36:52.900
[Guest]: Assam then included everything up to the Burma border, an 800 kilometer stretch of it, which

00:36:52.900 --> 00:36:56.860
[Guest]: was actually operated by the Americans themselves directly, right.

00:36:56.860 --> 00:37:01.040
[Guest]: So the Americans actually very heavily engaged, you know, they took over the sort of operations

00:37:01.040 --> 00:37:03.100
[Guest]: of the Calcutta port to a considerable extent, right.

00:37:03.100 --> 00:37:06.140
[Guest]: So they were very, very deeply involved in the subcontinent.

00:37:06.140 --> 00:37:10.220
[Guest]: For the first time, you know, thousands of Americans actually saw the subcontinent soldiers

00:37:10.220 --> 00:37:11.940
[Guest]: came here, lived here.

00:37:11.940 --> 00:37:17.340
[Guest]: So in that sense, I think the Second World War really marks an important sort of rupture

00:37:17.340 --> 00:37:18.340
[Amit Varma]: with everything.

00:37:18.340 --> 00:37:21.500
[Amit Varma]: And do you think that sympathetic position that the Americans took and the interventions

00:37:21.500 --> 00:37:25.660
[Amit Varma]: they made to Churchill had any role to play in making India's independence more probable?

00:37:25.660 --> 00:37:30.300
[Guest]: Well, I mean, I think the fact was that the Cripps mission failed, as I said, in a sense

00:37:30.300 --> 00:37:32.460
[Guest]: that you wouldn't have any immediate resolution.

00:37:32.460 --> 00:37:35.660
[Guest]: But the mere fact that the British had to send out a mission and agree that India's

00:37:35.660 --> 00:37:39.340
[Guest]: independence was on the cards meant that whenever the war came to an end, you are not going

00:37:39.340 --> 00:37:43.340
[Guest]: to have a situation where the British could reasonably expect to dial back from that.

00:37:43.340 --> 00:37:48.340
[Guest]: I think given the scale of India's commitment during the Second World War, given the scale

00:37:48.340 --> 00:37:54.180
[Guest]: of sacrifices made by India during that period, I mean, just in terms of simple financial

00:37:54.180 --> 00:38:02.020
[Guest]: transactions, you know, at the end of the Second World War, Britain owed India 3 billion

00:38:02.020 --> 00:38:06.940
[Guest]: pounds, now, which in today's currency is like the equivalent of 300 billion US dollars.

00:38:06.940 --> 00:38:10.060
[Guest]: You know, that was the amount of money that Britain owed to India for the war effort of

00:38:10.060 --> 00:38:11.060
[Guest]: India, right?

00:38:11.060 --> 00:38:13.580
[Guest]: So it's an extraordinary sort of mobilization of a very poor country.

00:38:13.580 --> 00:38:17.140
[Amit Varma]: Which India of course wanted to use to rebuild its economy and so on and that didn't work

00:38:17.140 --> 00:38:18.140
[Amit Varma]: out.

00:38:18.140 --> 00:38:19.140
[Guest]: Yeah, that didn't work out.

00:38:19.140 --> 00:38:23.340
[Guest]: So in a sense, you know, you had this extraordinary sort of, you know, transformation of the relationship

00:38:23.340 --> 00:38:26.500
[Guest]: between Britain and India, which had happened during the course of the war.

00:38:26.500 --> 00:38:30.040
[Guest]: So it was going to be very difficult for anyone to dial back from there.

00:38:30.040 --> 00:38:32.980
[Guest]: But nevertheless, by the time the war comes to an end, the Americans are actually quite

00:38:32.980 --> 00:38:37.020
[Guest]: happy to let the British sort of run the subcontinental affairs because they are just too engaged

00:38:37.020 --> 00:38:41.020
[Guest]: on what is happening in Europe, you know, whether the sort of, you know, the post war

00:38:41.020 --> 00:38:44.020
[Guest]: period and you know, the onset of the Cold War, etc.

00:38:44.020 --> 00:38:47.660
[Guest]: As well as East Asia, with the occupations of Japan, Korea, you know, various kinds of

00:38:47.660 --> 00:38:48.660
[Guest]: things happening.

00:38:48.660 --> 00:38:51.820
[Guest]: The Americans are actually quite happy to let the British sort of come back into free

00:38:51.820 --> 00:38:52.820
[Guest]: air.

00:38:52.820 --> 00:38:57.900
[Guest]: And it's not really until the Korean War of 1950-53 that the Americans then decide to

00:38:57.900 --> 00:39:02.900
[Guest]: displace the British and take a much more direct active role in the affairs of the subcontinent.

00:39:02.900 --> 00:39:06.740
[Amit Varma]: I think World War Two is an apt time to take a quick commercial break.

00:39:06.740 --> 00:39:09.300
[Unknown]: Hello, hello, hello, everybody.

00:39:09.300 --> 00:39:11.020
