00:40:04.620 --> 00:40:05.780
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the Scene and the Unseen.

00:40:05.780 --> 00:40:10.340
[Amit Varma]: I'm here with Srinath Raghavan and we're talking about US attitude towards South Asia.

00:40:10.340 --> 00:40:13.820
[Amit Varma]: Srinath, you were saying that, you know, we were talking about how the US was focused

00:40:13.820 --> 00:40:18.660
[Amit Varma]: on, you know, became refocused on South Asia during World War Two after this long period

00:40:18.660 --> 00:40:25.020
[Amit Varma]: of isolationism because India was both an important front in the war per se with, you

00:40:25.020 --> 00:40:29.540
[Amit Varma]: know, worries about Japan invading and also because things I guess had reached that stage

00:40:29.540 --> 00:40:33.380
[Amit Varma]: in the popular imagination where Gandhi was a popular figure and there was widespread

00:40:33.380 --> 00:40:35.280
[Amit Varma]: support for Indian independence.

00:40:35.280 --> 00:40:41.300
[Amit Varma]: But after the war, you know, America sort of turns his gaze away from South Asia and

00:40:41.300 --> 00:40:43.340
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned two reasons for this.

00:40:43.340 --> 00:40:49.500
[Guest]: Yeah, so the primary reason, of course, is the Americans are very preoccupied with much

00:40:49.500 --> 00:40:50.500
[Guest]: of the rest of the world, right?

00:40:50.500 --> 00:40:55.540
[Guest]: I mean, there is Western Europe and Eastern Europe, whose fate is yet to be decided.

00:40:55.540 --> 00:40:59.300
[Guest]: The reconstruction of these economies have to be undertaken.

00:40:59.300 --> 00:41:04.780
[Guest]: There is American sort of occupation in East Asia of Japan, Korea.

00:41:04.780 --> 00:41:08.940
[Guest]: All of these are things which take up a lot more time and attention.

00:41:08.940 --> 00:41:12.580
[Guest]: And the Americans are reasonably happy to let the British come back.

00:41:12.580 --> 00:41:18.420
[Guest]: The Americans support broadly the attempts by the British in 1946 to actually keep India

00:41:18.420 --> 00:41:19.420
[Guest]: together.

00:41:19.420 --> 00:41:23.340
[Guest]: I know it, which, you know, in India, we tend to assume that the British always wanted to

00:41:23.340 --> 00:41:24.340
[Guest]: partition India.

00:41:24.340 --> 00:41:28.220
[Guest]: I mean, whatever be the divide and rule policy over a longer frame, the fact was that in

00:41:28.220 --> 00:41:33.420
[Guest]: 1946, the British did want to keep India together, principally because India had proved to be

00:41:33.420 --> 00:41:36.780
[Guest]: such a great strategic asset to the British Empire during the Second World War.

00:41:36.780 --> 00:41:40.460
[Guest]: So because partition of India would have meant partition of the Indian Army, right?

00:41:40.460 --> 00:41:43.620
[Guest]: So that was something the British were desperately trying to avoid.

00:41:43.620 --> 00:41:45.700
[Guest]: And then the Americans were happy to sort of support that line.

00:41:45.700 --> 00:41:50.140
[Guest]: And ultimately, of course, when partition kind of became inevitable, they went along

00:41:50.140 --> 00:41:51.140
[Guest]: with it.

00:41:51.140 --> 00:41:55.700
[Guest]: But again, in a sense, even subsequently, Americans would regret the fact that they

00:41:55.700 --> 00:41:59.820
[Guest]: allowed the British to in some ways lead them by their noses, especially say when the Kashmir

00:41:59.820 --> 00:42:04.500
[Guest]: issue came before the UN Security Council in 1948.

00:42:04.500 --> 00:42:10.060
[Guest]: The American position on that particular dispute, which was very strongly shaped by British,

00:42:10.060 --> 00:42:15.140
[Guest]: who in turn had wider concerns about Muslim populations in Palestine and what would happen

00:42:15.140 --> 00:42:18.420
[Guest]: if they were seen as opposing Pakistan on this particular issue, because Kashmir was

00:42:18.420 --> 00:42:19.940
[Guest]: a Muslim majority state and so on, right?

00:42:19.940 --> 00:42:20.940
[Amit Varma]: So the British had a very...

00:42:20.940 --> 00:42:23.940
[Amit Varma]: And the Americans were just like, hey, you guys know Kashmir better, so we'll defer to

00:42:23.940 --> 00:42:24.940
[Guest]: you.

00:42:24.940 --> 00:42:25.940
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:42:25.940 --> 00:42:26.940
[Amit Varma]: So they just allowed them to sort of do that.

00:42:26.940 --> 00:42:30.540
[Guest]: And in some ways, you know, subsequently, Americans would say that, listen, maybe that

00:42:30.540 --> 00:42:32.080
[Guest]: was not the best thing to do.

00:42:32.080 --> 00:42:37.540
[Guest]: But nevertheless, given the range of other claims on their time and attention and energy,

00:42:37.540 --> 00:42:39.460
[Guest]: that is what the Americans ended up doing.

00:42:39.460 --> 00:42:45.420
[Guest]: And as I said, you know, things only start changing from the second half of 1950, when

00:42:45.420 --> 00:42:47.480
[Guest]: North Korea attacked South Korea.

00:42:47.480 --> 00:42:53.620
[Guest]: And there is now a major concern that the Soviet Union might actually strike similarly

00:42:53.620 --> 00:42:57.380
[Guest]: at other places, particularly in the Persian Gulf, which was seen as very vulnerable.

00:42:57.380 --> 00:43:01.140
[Guest]: And in that context, Americans then start thinking seriously about building alliances

00:43:01.140 --> 00:43:05.660
[Guest]: to contain the Soviet Union in the Middle East and in Southeast Asia.

00:43:05.660 --> 00:43:10.180
[Guest]: And in both these contexts, funnily enough, it's Pakistan, which is seen as the more chosen

00:43:10.180 --> 00:43:11.180
[Guest]: partner.

00:43:11.180 --> 00:43:16.260
[Guest]: And again, there, you know, you can talk about how the sort of stereotypical images of Hindus

00:43:16.260 --> 00:43:19.420
[Guest]: and Muslims then gets transposed on to Indians and Pakistanis.

00:43:19.420 --> 00:43:23.820
[Guest]: And Muslims being virile and warriors and Hindus being shifty and shady.

00:43:23.820 --> 00:43:25.380
[Guest]: Effent and, you know, incapable.

00:43:25.380 --> 00:43:26.380
[Guest]: The kipling sort of.

00:43:26.380 --> 00:43:27.380
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:43:27.380 --> 00:43:28.380
[Guest]: Right.

00:43:28.380 --> 00:43:30.620
[Guest]: And what is interesting to me, and again, you know, these are the things that you learn

00:43:30.620 --> 00:43:36.500
[Guest]: just by doing research, is how striking are those sort of tropes and themes and, you know,

00:43:36.500 --> 00:43:40.420
[Guest]: those codes of thinking about this part of the world, you know, which go back to this

00:43:40.420 --> 00:43:41.420
[Guest]: literature.

00:43:41.420 --> 00:43:43.580
[Guest]: I mean, like kipling, for instance, I mean, like generations of Americans only knew the

00:43:43.580 --> 00:43:45.220
[Guest]: subcontinent through kipling, right?

00:43:45.220 --> 00:43:50.420
[Guest]: In that sense, you know, the influence of those ways of thinking was very strong.

00:43:50.420 --> 00:43:56.740
[Guest]: So in a sense, and, you know, it is interesting that when the US-Pakistan alliance is concluded

00:43:56.740 --> 00:44:01.460
[Guest]: in 1954, the Americans do hardly any serious assessment of what is it that Pakistan is

00:44:01.460 --> 00:44:05.460
[Guest]: going to do for them by way of this alliance, except for assuming that Pakistan has somehow

00:44:05.460 --> 00:44:10.380
[Guest]: a very great supply of, you know, Punjabi Muslims who can be fielded in uniforms against

00:44:10.380 --> 00:44:12.940
[Guest]: the Red Army or somebody else.

00:44:12.940 --> 00:44:16.540
[Guest]: And that, you know, this is, these are people who are sort of predisposed to fight in a

00:44:16.540 --> 00:44:17.540
[Guest]: way that India.

00:44:17.540 --> 00:44:21.300
[Guest]: And of course, there is a political problem as well, which is that India is non-aligned.

00:44:21.300 --> 00:44:26.500
[Guest]: Jawaharlal Nehru has his own sort of views on the United States and its policies in Asia.

00:44:26.500 --> 00:44:31.100
[Guest]: And that also adds to the sort of, you know, the sort of growing gulf between India and

00:44:31.100 --> 00:44:32.100
[Amit Varma]: the United States.

00:44:32.100 --> 00:44:35.780
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that struck me was that at the moment of independence, you could probably

00:44:35.780 --> 00:44:39.980
[Amit Varma]: say that there's a sort of a blank slate in South Asia, that Pakistan, India, they can

00:44:39.980 --> 00:44:41.540
[Amit Varma]: turn whichever way.

00:44:41.540 --> 00:44:46.020
[Amit Varma]: And at that point, Jinnah sort of takes a practical real politic view, he sees what

00:44:46.020 --> 00:44:50.720
[Amit Varma]: is happening with, you know, that the US would need a counterpoint to the Soviet Union.

00:44:50.720 --> 00:44:54.980
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, you quote him as telling Margaret Bourke-White, quote, America needs Pakistan

00:44:54.980 --> 00:44:57.420
[Amit Varma]: more than Pakistan needs America, unquote.

00:44:57.420 --> 00:45:00.540
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you know, there are those overtures towards America.

00:45:00.540 --> 00:45:05.920
[Amit Varma]: And in contrast, Nehru basically alienates the US in three ways.

00:45:05.920 --> 00:45:10.260
[Amit Varma]: Number one, he has this whole philosophical approach that Asia is for Asians.

00:45:10.260 --> 00:45:14.420
[Amit Varma]: So getting rid of colonialism doesn't only mean getting rid of the British, it means

00:45:14.420 --> 00:45:16.220
[Amit Varma]: Asia is for Asians.

00:45:16.220 --> 00:45:20.260
[Amit Varma]: The second approach is, of course, his whole approach towards a mixed economy and import

00:45:20.260 --> 00:45:25.220
[Amit Varma]: substitution and so on, which doesn't at that time, align with the Americans ideology.

00:45:25.220 --> 00:45:27.900
[Amit Varma]: And again, here again, ideology sort of coming into it.

00:45:27.900 --> 00:45:32.340
[Amit Varma]: And the third is simply his personal arrogance towards Americans, because, you know, a lot

00:45:32.340 --> 00:45:36.900
[Amit Varma]: of these early Indian freedom fighters were also in a sense, British liberals.

00:45:36.900 --> 00:45:41.180
[Amit Varma]: And he takes that kind of snobbishness and attitude to his approach with the Americans.

00:45:41.180 --> 00:45:42.180
[Guest]: That's right.

00:45:42.180 --> 00:45:46.580
[Guest]: I think it's fair to say that, you know, all of the things that you mentioned are very

00:45:46.580 --> 00:45:51.180
[Guest]: important issues in the way that US India relations unfolded in this early period.

00:45:51.180 --> 00:45:55.540
[Guest]: Pakistan, you know, made a pitch for American assistance pretty quickly, you know, even

00:45:55.540 --> 00:45:59.580
[Guest]: though for all of Janaz Bravado, I mean, the fact was that Pakistanis desperately needed

00:45:59.580 --> 00:46:00.580
[Guest]: this thing.

00:46:00.580 --> 00:46:04.660
[Guest]: And at that point of time, their concern was not so much military sort of counterweight

00:46:04.660 --> 00:46:08.260
[Guest]: against India as economic aid, because it was a new state which is being created and

00:46:08.260 --> 00:46:09.260
[Guest]: so on.

00:46:09.260 --> 00:46:12.900
[Guest]: But of course, once the Kashmir issue came to the fore, and India and Pakistan were locked

00:46:12.900 --> 00:46:17.460
[Guest]: in this sort of antagonism and were fighting a war and so on, it became clear to the Pakistanis

00:46:17.460 --> 00:46:23.740
[Guest]: that in order to offset India's sort of superior military and economic capabilities, they needed

00:46:23.740 --> 00:46:25.340
[Guest]: some kind of a counterweight.

00:46:25.340 --> 00:46:28.940
[Guest]: So you have this sort of wooing of the Americans, which happens in the context of the Korean

00:46:28.940 --> 00:46:30.100
[Guest]: War, etc.

00:46:30.100 --> 00:46:31.980
[Guest]: culminating in the thing, right?

00:46:31.980 --> 00:46:35.860
[Guest]: The second point is about economic philosophies and so on.

00:46:35.860 --> 00:46:40.580
[Guest]: And again, what is interesting in the early period is that, yes, you know, as early as

00:46:40.580 --> 00:46:44.460
[Guest]: 1939, when the Second World War was beginning, the Americans are, at least parts of the State

00:46:44.460 --> 00:46:48.500
[Guest]: Department are starting to think about what do we need for the post-war world, right?

00:46:48.500 --> 00:46:52.780
[Guest]: And one of the things that is very strong in American thinking is that the post-war

00:46:52.780 --> 00:46:56.740
[Guest]: world should not have the problems that the interwar period had.

00:46:56.740 --> 00:47:00.860
[Guest]: And they believe that one of the major reasons why you had this kind of aggression by Japan,

00:47:00.860 --> 00:47:05.860
[Guest]: Germany, etc., was that the global economy had been broken up into various kinds of autarkic

00:47:05.860 --> 00:47:06.860
[Guest]: blocks.

00:47:06.860 --> 00:47:09.820
[Guest]: And one of those autarkic blocks, incidentally, during the Great Depression was that of the

00:47:09.820 --> 00:47:10.820
[Guest]: British Commonwealth, right?

00:47:10.820 --> 00:47:15.100
[Guest]: So, which is one of the – so opening up the British Commonwealth countries like India

00:47:15.100 --> 00:47:18.580
[Guest]: and integrating them with the global markets was a very important part of the American

00:47:18.580 --> 00:47:19.940
[Guest]: vision for the post-war world, right?

00:47:19.940 --> 00:47:23.860
[Guest]: So the United States wanted very much to keep India in the capitalist sort of the thing

00:47:23.860 --> 00:47:27.860
[Guest]: and believed that India has to be an important part of that story.

00:47:27.860 --> 00:47:29.500
[Guest]: So the Americans were willing to cut India a lot of slack.

00:47:29.500 --> 00:47:34.780
[Guest]: I mean, I don't think the problem was as much about India adopting a planned economic

00:47:34.780 --> 00:47:36.980
[Guest]: growth model or even a mixed economy.

00:47:36.980 --> 00:47:41.420
[Guest]: As with many of their other allies, the Americans were willing to sort of give a lot of, you

00:47:41.420 --> 00:47:45.780
[Guest]: know, ground to countries to decide what was working for them, because their ultimate aim

00:47:45.780 --> 00:47:50.180
[Guest]: was to ensure reconstruction, development and integration in a capitalist rather than

00:47:50.180 --> 00:47:51.460
[Guest]: the socialist frame, right?

00:47:51.460 --> 00:47:53.980
[Guest]: So that was the broader consideration.

00:47:53.980 --> 00:47:59.740
[Guest]: But I think the, you know, there were issues over, say, American investments in the subcontinent,

00:47:59.740 --> 00:48:04.620
[Guest]: which was interestingly enough, you know, opposed not just by the political class, but

00:48:04.620 --> 00:48:05.740
[Guest]: by the Indian business community, right?

00:48:05.740 --> 00:48:09.420
[Guest]: I mean, if you think of all the people who wrote the Bombay Plan of 1944, they were the

00:48:09.420 --> 00:48:14.540
[Guest]: same people who are constantly reminding Jawaharlal Nehru that, you know, do not, you know, liberalize

00:48:14.540 --> 00:48:16.460
[Guest]: your sort of industrial policy, etc.

00:48:16.460 --> 00:48:19.580
[Guest]: Because they thought that India has to have the space for Indian capitalism to come up.

00:48:19.580 --> 00:48:22.900
[Amit Varma]: Well, out of self-interest, because they wanted to protect their own interest.

00:48:22.900 --> 00:48:26.500
[Guest]: And then they believe that, you know, so far, the experience of having been working with

00:48:26.500 --> 00:48:30.380
[Guest]: British capital in India in such a big way, was that Indian capital is always sort of,

00:48:30.380 --> 00:48:31.820
[Guest]: you know, never allowed to grow.

00:48:31.820 --> 00:48:35.780
[Guest]: And they believe that this independence also meant an opportunity to create a national

00:48:35.780 --> 00:48:40.860
[Guest]: economic space with an Indian sort of capitalist sort of lead development happening, right?

00:48:40.860 --> 00:48:42.820
[Guest]: So there was that kind of a thing.

00:48:42.820 --> 00:48:44.980
[Guest]: But the Americans also had other kinds of differences with India, right?

00:48:44.980 --> 00:48:48.620
[Guest]: For instance, Americans throughout the first and the second five year plan, which if you

00:48:48.620 --> 00:48:54.020
[Guest]: say is the first decade after Indian independence, really, through the 1950s, were insisting

00:48:54.020 --> 00:48:57.780
[Guest]: that India was focusing too much on heavy industrialization, not paying enough attention

00:48:57.780 --> 00:48:59.580
[Guest]: to agriculture, right?

00:48:59.580 --> 00:49:03.540
[Guest]: And even though India did not actually go with American priorities, Americans gave enormous

00:49:03.540 --> 00:49:04.540
[Guest]: amounts of economic aid to India.

00:49:04.540 --> 00:49:07.660
[Guest]: I mean, if you think of something like the second five year plan, you know, there were

00:49:07.660 --> 00:49:11.700
[Guest]: such large financing gaps in the plan that even the planners themselves assumed that

00:49:11.700 --> 00:49:15.500
[Guest]: this money would materialize from somewhere and that somewhere was the United States of

00:49:15.500 --> 00:49:18.220
[Guest]: America, which was only dollar surplus country, so to speak.

00:49:18.220 --> 00:49:22.420
[Guest]: So in that context, Americans were willing to sort of, you know, despite these differences,

00:49:22.420 --> 00:49:24.140
[Guest]: they would have sort of accommodated.

00:49:24.140 --> 00:49:28.060
[Guest]: The third point which is saying is quite interesting and important, which is about Jawaharlal

00:49:28.060 --> 00:49:31.740
[Guest]: Nehru's attitudes towards the United States and its policies in Asia, but also towards

00:49:31.740 --> 00:49:33.980
[Guest]: the United States itself, right?

00:49:33.980 --> 00:49:40.220
[Guest]: So on the policy front, I think it's fair to say that Nehru believed that the United

00:49:40.220 --> 00:49:46.200
[Guest]: States, you know, in the post war period was in effect, creating divisions amongst Asian

00:49:46.200 --> 00:49:51.080
[Guest]: countries by continuing to hold on to military bases in Japan and other places.

00:49:51.080 --> 00:49:54.720
[Guest]: And that US policy in some ways was a very sort of destabilizing element in this region.

00:49:54.720 --> 00:49:59.500
[Guest]: And that was a major source of sort of, you know, clash of worldviews, so to speak, between

00:49:59.500 --> 00:50:00.500
[Guest]: these two countries.

00:50:00.500 --> 00:50:03.460
[Guest]: And of course, you know, Jawaharlal Nehru, as you rightly point out, I think it's fair

00:50:03.460 --> 00:50:11.340
[Guest]: to say, had, you know, had a degree of contempt for the Americans as a bunch of parvenu capitalists,

00:50:11.340 --> 00:50:14.780
[Guest]: you know, which mirrored the attitudes of the British aristocracy more than that of

00:50:14.780 --> 00:50:15.780
[Guest]: anything else.

00:50:15.780 --> 00:50:21.940
[Guest]: In fact, there is a very oft quoted line in the memoirs of Dean Acheson, who was President

00:50:21.940 --> 00:50:25.420
[Guest]: Truman's Secretary of State, and he says that, you know, when I met Jawaharlal Nehru, I was

00:50:25.420 --> 00:50:30.020
[Guest]: reminded of Queen Victoria's statement about Prime Minister William Gladstone.

00:50:30.020 --> 00:50:33.660
[Guest]: And she said that he spoke to me as if he was addressing a public meeting.

00:50:33.660 --> 00:50:37.460
[Guest]: And you know, in a sense, that's the way that we felt about Jawaharlal Nehru as well.

00:50:37.460 --> 00:50:41.100
[Guest]: So there was definitely that kind of a cultural gulf as well.

00:50:41.100 --> 00:50:45.460
[Amit Varma]: And Nehru once very condescendingly told JRD Tata, do not speak to me of profit, it is

00:50:45.460 --> 00:50:46.540
[Amit Varma]: a dirty word.

00:50:46.540 --> 00:50:50.180
[Amit Varma]: And I suppose that attitude carries through to how he looked at American capitalism.

00:50:50.180 --> 00:50:54.780
[Amit Varma]: But also, perhaps there is some amount of animus, as you've pointed out in the book,

00:50:54.780 --> 00:50:59.380
[Amit Varma]: through, you know, incidents like, for example, the denial of the sterling that was owed to

00:50:59.380 --> 00:51:03.660
[Amit Varma]: India, which, you know, which America kind of supported that not being given to India.

00:51:03.660 --> 00:51:06.720
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, that's one reason to hold a grudge.

00:51:06.720 --> 00:51:10.300
[Amit Varma]: Another reason to hold a grudge is the stand that America took on Kashmir, where they just

00:51:10.300 --> 00:51:14.220
[Amit Varma]: supported the British, which, you know, in retrospect, like you said, it's completely

00:51:14.220 --> 00:51:18.980
[Amit Varma]: reasonable, but Nehru sitting at that vantage point of history probably did not view it

00:51:18.980 --> 00:51:21.420
[Amit Varma]: in that way and, you know, just saw them as the enemy.

00:51:21.420 --> 00:51:22.420
[Guest]: Yeah, that's right.

00:51:22.420 --> 00:51:26.860
[Guest]: And I think in general, the American decision to align with Pakistan in 1954, in some ways

00:51:26.860 --> 00:51:31.740
[Guest]: was a major turning point in their engagement with the subcontinent, not just with India,

00:51:31.740 --> 00:51:32.740
[Guest]: right.

00:51:32.740 --> 00:51:36.820
[Guest]: So of course, India Pakistan relations over Kashmir and, you know, and then the American

00:51:36.820 --> 00:51:39.940
[Guest]: alliance had an impact on India US relations.

00:51:39.940 --> 00:51:42.900
[Guest]: But we also forget there was a second non aligned country in the subcontinent, Afghanistan

00:51:42.900 --> 00:51:46.620
[Guest]: at that point of time, which also had very serious problems with Pakistan, primarily

00:51:46.620 --> 00:51:51.100
[Guest]: over this, you know, disputed boundary area, which they refer to as Pashtunistan, where

00:51:51.100 --> 00:51:54.780
[Guest]: the community called Pashtuns used to live on either side of that.

00:51:54.780 --> 00:51:59.780
[Guest]: And there was a fairly strong Pashtun nationalist sentiment on either side, including such stalwart

00:51:59.780 --> 00:52:03.980
[Guest]: people as Khan Abdul Ghaffar Khan, who was known as frontier Gandhi, who was a sort of

00:52:03.980 --> 00:52:08.100
[Guest]: a major advocate of the sort of Pashtun unity movement.

00:52:08.100 --> 00:52:12.020
[Guest]: And we also, you know, should recall that Afghanistan was one of the few countries which

00:52:12.020 --> 00:52:15.460
[Guest]: opposed the entry of Pakistan into the United Nations in 1948.

00:52:15.460 --> 00:52:18.420
[Guest]: So you know, the animosity was actually pretty strong there.

00:52:18.420 --> 00:52:23.020
[Guest]: And you had a parallel development in Afghan Pakistan relations, as what happened with

00:52:23.020 --> 00:52:28.060
[Guest]: India Pakistan relations, where American alliance with Pakistan in some ways, really throws

00:52:28.060 --> 00:52:29.580
[Guest]: the Afghans off the rails.

00:52:29.580 --> 00:52:33.340
[Guest]: And of course, we must remember that in that case, they were the weaker of the two parties.

00:52:33.340 --> 00:52:38.260
[Guest]: So in a sense, you have a strange constellation of India and Afghanistan on either side of

00:52:38.260 --> 00:52:41.540
[Guest]: Pakistan, both of which are ostensibly non aligned countries.

00:52:41.540 --> 00:52:47.060
[Guest]: But after the Americans sort of drive towards forging an alliance with Pakistan, end up

00:52:47.060 --> 00:52:49.060
[Guest]: building ties with the Soviet Union, right.

00:52:49.060 --> 00:52:52.740
[Guest]: And that, of course, coincides with the rise of Nikita Khrushchev, who's also open to dealing

00:52:52.740 --> 00:52:57.740
[Guest]: with non aligned countries is not as ideologically sort of minded as Stalin was and had a more

00:52:57.740 --> 00:53:00.700
[Guest]: pragmatic view of what the Soviet Union wanted to do.

00:53:00.700 --> 00:53:05.060
[Guest]: And in some ways, you know, the US sort of alliance with Pakistan really draws a line

00:53:05.060 --> 00:53:06.060
[Guest]: through the subcontinent.

00:53:06.060 --> 00:53:10.460
[Amit Varma]: And it makes it inevitable that India and Afghanistan then have no choice, they have

00:53:10.460 --> 00:53:12.780
[Amit Varma]: to sort of gravitate towards the Soviet Union eventually.

00:53:12.780 --> 00:53:16.740
[Guest]: Yeah, so you know, as historians are generally sort of very averse to saying anything was

00:53:16.740 --> 00:53:17.740
[Guest]: inevitable.

00:53:17.740 --> 00:53:21.180
[Guest]: So I think, yeah, it's, it's, it's, it's, in a sense, the logic of it then becomes difficult

00:53:21.180 --> 00:53:25.260
[Guest]: to escape, especially when you have a leader like Khrushchev, who is willing to sort of

00:53:25.260 --> 00:53:26.260
[Guest]: give you things, right.

00:53:26.260 --> 00:53:30.140
[Guest]: See, with someone like Stalin, for instance, you know, India had absolutely no relationship

00:53:30.140 --> 00:53:34.900
[Guest]: with the Soviet Union in the first, you know, five, six years after Indian independence.

00:53:34.900 --> 00:53:38.700
[Guest]: Because there was an Indian Communist Party, which was opposed to Indian Azadi and stuff.

00:53:38.700 --> 00:53:43.080
[Guest]: And this, you know, the government was cracking down on them at home.

00:53:43.080 --> 00:53:46.580
[Guest]: So there's no question of sort of having any good relationship with Soviet Union.

00:53:46.580 --> 00:53:49.860
[Guest]: You know, Nehru sent his own sister Vijayalakshmi Pandit as ambassador to Soviet Union.

00:53:49.860 --> 00:53:51.700
[Guest]: She never even got to meet Stalin.

00:53:51.700 --> 00:53:55.200
[Guest]: The first Indian ambassador who ever got to meet Stalin was Sarvapalli Radhakrishnan.

00:53:55.200 --> 00:53:58.200
[Guest]: And that Radhakrishnan was, you know, more or less sort of bulldozed his way through

00:53:58.200 --> 00:54:00.420
[Guest]: and had a chat with Stalin and so on, right.

00:54:00.420 --> 00:54:05.860
[Guest]: It's only after Stalin's death, that there is a slow reorientation of Soviet attitudes

00:54:05.860 --> 00:54:07.260
[Guest]: towards India.

00:54:07.260 --> 00:54:10.740
[Guest]: So in a sense, you know, if it was not just because of what Americans did, but also what

00:54:10.740 --> 00:54:11.740
[Guest]: was happening in the Soviet Union.

00:54:11.740 --> 00:54:18.540
[Guest]: So you had this, once again, a constellation of things, which brings India and Afghanistan,

00:54:18.540 --> 00:54:21.220
[Guest]: you know, in a much more favorable relationship with the Soviet Union.

00:54:21.220 --> 00:54:24.100
[Guest]: The Soviet Union is willing to sort of bankroll things in Afghanistan, they're willing to

00:54:24.100 --> 00:54:25.580
[Guest]: bankroll things in India.

00:54:25.580 --> 00:54:28.580
[Guest]: But at least as far as India is concerned, the United States, however, continued to remain

00:54:28.580 --> 00:54:30.980
[Guest]: much more important in economic terms.

00:54:30.980 --> 00:54:34.180
[Guest]: You know, we tend to think of the Indian economy as somehow being very influenced by the Soviet

00:54:34.180 --> 00:54:35.180
[Guest]: model and so on.

00:54:35.180 --> 00:54:36.500
[Guest]: I think that's actually fundamentally wrong.

00:54:36.500 --> 00:54:40.460
[Guest]: There are aspects also with planned economy model, which we did take in, especially ideas

00:54:40.460 --> 00:54:41.460
[Guest]: like the plan frame.

00:54:41.460 --> 00:54:46.340
[Guest]: But you know, a lot of your economic plans were vetted by American economists who used

00:54:46.340 --> 00:54:49.500
[Guest]: to come to India, who used to stay and spend time as actors consultants to your planning

00:54:49.500 --> 00:54:50.500
[Guest]: commission.

00:54:50.500 --> 00:54:53.860
[Guest]: So and then the Americans, as I said, you know, were very important in bridging the

00:54:53.860 --> 00:54:57.180
[Guest]: financial deficit, which our plans had almost from the very beginning.

00:54:57.180 --> 00:54:59.340
[Amit Varma]: Right, we'll cover the economics later.

00:54:59.340 --> 00:55:05.780
[Amit Varma]: But that whole decision of the US to sort of adopt Pakistan in a sense also sets a permanent

00:55:05.780 --> 00:55:06.780
[Amit Varma]: dissonance in place.

00:55:06.780 --> 00:55:10.580
[Amit Varma]: And that dissonance is in fact, reflected in the title of your book itself.

00:55:10.580 --> 00:55:14.380
[Amit Varma]: You know, Bill Clinton had once called the Pakistan Afghanistan border the most dangerous

00:55:14.380 --> 00:55:15.580
[Amit Varma]: place in the world.

00:55:15.580 --> 00:55:19.300
[Amit Varma]: And Obama had later used the same phrase for the India Pakistan border.

00:55:19.300 --> 00:55:24.460
[Amit Varma]: And the American approaches to these two borders, in terms of principles, is completely different.

00:55:24.460 --> 00:55:27.900
[Amit Varma]: That on the one hand, when it comes to the border with India, they'll support the whole

00:55:27.900 --> 00:55:31.900
[Amit Varma]: Kashmir movement, you know, which Pakistan is deeply interested in.

00:55:31.900 --> 00:55:35.080
[Amit Varma]: But on the other border, they won't support the Pashtunistan movement.

00:55:35.080 --> 00:55:40.340
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, on one border, they are very concerned about clamping down on terror entirely.

00:55:40.340 --> 00:55:44.900
[Amit Varma]: And on the other border for a long time, it was kind of a wink and not kind of thing that

00:55:44.900 --> 00:55:46.900
[Amit Varma]: you sort of let it happen.

00:55:46.900 --> 00:55:51.260
[Amit Varma]: And would you say that this is something that kind of began at that period and has continued

00:55:51.260 --> 00:55:56.020
[Amit Varma]: since and this is a sort of a dissonance that it's hard to come to terms with?

00:55:56.020 --> 00:55:57.360
[Guest]: Yeah, it is.

00:55:57.360 --> 00:56:01.740
[Guest]: But from the American point of view, you know, it's rarely the case that in international

00:56:01.740 --> 00:56:04.580
[Guest]: politics, you're going to be able to apply the same principles in all places, right.

00:56:04.580 --> 00:56:08.940
[Guest]: And in fact, I quote one of the Americans as telling the Afghans that, listen, we were

00:56:08.940 --> 00:56:10.940
[Guest]: the ones who invented the term self determination.

00:56:10.940 --> 00:56:14.260
[Guest]: We can also tell you that doesn't apply to the Pashtuns.

00:56:14.260 --> 00:56:18.980
[Guest]: So in a sense, obviously, larger political and other kinds of interests do come to the

00:56:18.980 --> 00:56:19.980
[Guest]: fore.

00:56:19.980 --> 00:56:25.540
[Guest]: But at the same time, I think it's fair to say that at least after 1963, the Americans

00:56:25.540 --> 00:56:28.300
[Guest]: made no serious attempt to sort of intervene in the Kashmir dispute.

00:56:28.300 --> 00:56:33.580
[Guest]: 1963 really was the last time because India in the wake of the war with China and the

00:56:33.580 --> 00:56:37.340
[Guest]: defeat against China was looking to the United States for military supplies.

00:56:37.340 --> 00:56:41.340
[Guest]: The United States was, Kennedy administration was giving those military supplies.

00:56:41.340 --> 00:56:45.700
[Guest]: The Pakistanis and Ayub Khan protested and the Americans felt that maybe this is a good

00:56:45.700 --> 00:56:51.060
[Guest]: opportunity to try and see if some kind of a solution could be done in Kashmir.

00:56:51.060 --> 00:56:54.420
[Guest]: And that broadly speaking was the last time the Americans actually directly ever get involved

00:56:54.420 --> 00:56:55.500
[Guest]: in that play, right.

00:56:55.500 --> 00:57:00.100
[Guest]: And their whole idea is that, listen, we need the subcontinent to be stable, which is to

00:57:00.100 --> 00:57:01.580
[Guest]: say we don't want wars.

00:57:01.580 --> 00:57:02.980
[Guest]: We don't want arms races out here.

00:57:02.980 --> 00:57:07.740
[Guest]: We want these countries to develop broadly on capitalist lines and clearly stay away

00:57:07.740 --> 00:57:08.740
[Guest]: from the Soviet camp, right.

00:57:08.740 --> 00:57:13.220
[Guest]: So in a sense, you had some kind of minimal objectives, which if they were met, you know,

00:57:13.220 --> 00:57:14.220
[Guest]: life would be going on.

00:57:14.220 --> 00:57:18.140
[Guest]: But then, of course, you know, a range of other concentrations come into play from the

00:57:18.140 --> 00:57:19.140
[Guest]: 1970s.

00:57:19.140 --> 00:57:23.140
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, Pakistan has been a failed state for so long that we don't realize that

00:57:23.140 --> 00:57:24.300
[Amit Varma]: it wasn't always thus.

00:57:24.300 --> 00:57:29.540
[Amit Varma]: And you point out that, you know, between 59 and 69, when Ayub Khan was in charge, Pakistan

00:57:29.540 --> 00:57:34.540
[Amit Varma]: pretty much took the economic direction which the US wanted them to take and it worked for

00:57:34.540 --> 00:57:35.540
[Guest]: them.

00:57:35.540 --> 00:57:36.540
[Guest]: They were doing well.

00:57:36.540 --> 00:57:37.540
[Guest]: Yeah, exactly.

00:57:37.540 --> 00:57:38.540
[Guest]: Right.

00:57:38.540 --> 00:57:40.820
[Guest]: I mean, you know, that decade in some ways is Ayub Khan was celebrating as this decade

00:57:40.820 --> 00:57:42.060
[Guest]: of development, of course.

00:57:42.060 --> 00:57:48.640
[Guest]: But the reality was that the Pakistanis were much more amenable to American suggestions

00:57:48.640 --> 00:57:51.600
[Guest]: on their models of planned economic development.

00:57:51.600 --> 00:57:55.700
[Guest]: The Pakistan Planning Commission was also very strongly supported by a group of economists

00:57:55.700 --> 00:57:58.700
[Guest]: based at Harvard called the Harvard Group of Economists.

00:57:58.700 --> 00:58:03.340
[Guest]: And in a sense, they undertook many of the things that India was not willing to take.

00:58:03.340 --> 00:58:06.940
[Guest]: For instance, Pakistan embraced the Green Revolution technologies before India did,

00:58:06.940 --> 00:58:09.860
[Guest]: right, and never quite faced the same degree of constraints.

00:58:09.860 --> 00:58:14.420
[Guest]: They allowed for a system of sort of, you know, put in place a fiscal infrastructure

00:58:14.420 --> 00:58:18.220
[Guest]: of tax breaks and such like things, which allowed for capital accumulation to happen

00:58:18.220 --> 00:58:19.220
[Guest]: much stronger.

00:58:19.220 --> 00:58:22.260
[Guest]: And this thing and Pakistan had access to certain kinds of markets.

00:58:22.260 --> 00:58:26.300
[Guest]: So that's a decade when you see Pakistan is actually economically doing better than India,

00:58:26.300 --> 00:58:29.140
[Guest]: at least in terms of growth rates and such like things.

00:58:29.140 --> 00:58:33.180
[Guest]: And there is a sense that, you know, you have a regime which might be authoritarian, but

00:58:33.180 --> 00:58:37.740
[Guest]: it's still delivering, right, which is the sort of model that American political scientists

00:58:37.740 --> 00:58:41.220
[Guest]: like Samuel Huntington actually hail as a good way of thinking about it, which is to

00:58:41.220 --> 00:58:45.340
[Guest]: say that what, you know, democracy and such like things may not be the most important

00:58:45.340 --> 00:58:47.020
[Guest]: thing for the developing world.

00:58:47.020 --> 00:58:51.220
[Guest]: It is stability, which is given by an authoritarian figure, who is nevertheless also a benevolent

00:58:51.220 --> 00:58:52.540
[Amit Varma]: authoritarian figure, because he can deliver.

00:58:52.540 --> 00:58:57.020
[Guest]: So sort of a redefinition of that manifest destiny where it's not just delivering liberty,

00:58:57.020 --> 00:58:59.420
[Guest]: but delivering whatever we feel the need.

00:58:59.420 --> 00:59:00.420
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:59:00.420 --> 00:59:02.660
[Guest]: So in essence, you have that kind of a thing and Pakistani thing.

00:59:02.660 --> 00:59:09.100
[Guest]: But what is also clear is that by the end of the decade, by 1969, the sort of the lopsidedness

00:59:09.100 --> 00:59:11.860
[Guest]: of the Pakistani growth story also comes to this thing, right?

00:59:11.860 --> 00:59:14.620
[Guest]: And that lopsidedness broadly happens along two axes.

00:59:14.620 --> 00:59:19.140
[Guest]: The first is that of sort of, you know, excessive concentration of wealth amongst a very small

00:59:19.140 --> 00:59:23.460
[Guest]: group of corporates and families really, I mean, like, you know, like the parts of the

00:59:23.460 --> 00:59:27.260
[Guest]: subcontinent family owned businesses is the model in Pakistan as well.

00:59:27.260 --> 00:59:32.140
[Guest]: And the Pakistan Planning Commission's head in 1968, actually discloses in an interview

00:59:32.140 --> 00:59:37.340
[Guest]: that you know, some 22 families in the country actually own over 95% of the wealth, right?

00:59:37.340 --> 00:59:41.560
[Guest]: I mean, and then it's a shocking thing because, you know, you had this.

00:59:41.560 --> 00:59:46.820
[Guest]: The second axis along which there is this kind of lopsided growth is the West Pakistan,

00:59:46.820 --> 00:59:52.260
[Guest]: which is Pakistan as we know it today, is getting much more of investment resources.

00:59:52.260 --> 00:59:55.300
[Guest]: Industrialization is happening there at a much stronger pace than what is happening

00:59:55.300 --> 00:59:57.220
[Guest]: in East Pakistan, today's Bangladesh.

00:59:57.220 --> 01:00:01.300
[Guest]: And that leads to a major gulf between the two wings of Pakistan.

01:00:01.300 --> 01:00:04.360
[Guest]: And it's interesting that the Pakistani Planning Commission is actually staffed almost entirely

01:00:04.360 --> 01:00:05.360
[Guest]: by Bengali economists, right?

01:00:05.360 --> 01:00:09.320
[Guest]: So the guys who are writing the plans know very well that, you know, these things are

01:00:09.320 --> 01:00:10.320
[Guest]: in some way.

01:00:10.320 --> 01:00:12.820
[Guest]: So they come up with this whole narrative of saying that, you know, this economic growth

01:00:12.820 --> 01:00:18.140
[Guest]: model is essentially neo-colonial, because we are providing agricultural sort of inputs

01:00:18.140 --> 01:00:21.740
[Guest]: and you know, all the investment and industrialization is happening in the West.

01:00:21.740 --> 01:00:26.580
[Guest]: And you know, that's supposed to be the sort of dependency model, you know, so to speak.

01:00:26.580 --> 01:00:32.980
[Guest]: So in a sense, the sort of American assisted economic policies do extract a toll.

01:00:32.980 --> 01:00:38.220
[Guest]: And that in some ways leads to the collapse of the Ayub Khan regime in 1969.

01:00:38.220 --> 01:00:41.620
[Guest]: The set of protests in both East and West Pakistan and leads to the overthrow of the

01:00:41.620 --> 01:00:43.140
[Guest]: military dictatorship.

01:00:43.140 --> 01:00:46.060
[Guest]: And then of course, that also sets in train a series of events which leads to the liberation

01:00:46.060 --> 01:00:47.420
[Guest]: of Bangladesh in 1971.

01:00:47.420 --> 01:00:50.580
[Amit Varma]: And according to you, and you've of course written a whole separate book on this, but

01:00:50.580 --> 01:00:54.340
[Amit Varma]: even in this book, you devote some time to it, that 71 is absolutely critical, not just

01:00:54.340 --> 01:00:59.500
[Amit Varma]: to the subcontinent itself in terms of India, Pakistan, Afghanistan, but also the way the

01:00:59.500 --> 01:01:01.340
[Amit Varma]: US perceives the region as a whole.

01:01:01.340 --> 01:01:06.300
[Amit Varma]: And of course, in the 70s, everything kind of changes, you know, where the Cold War becomes

01:01:06.300 --> 01:01:08.620
[Amit Varma]: less relevant and other factors come into play.

01:01:08.620 --> 01:01:09.620
[Guest]: That's right.

01:01:09.620 --> 01:01:13.700
[Guest]: And I think 71 is important because, you know, if you look at the period, say in the run

01:01:13.700 --> 01:01:20.180
[Guest]: up to the in the 1960s, right, I mean, especially the second half of the 1960s, the United States

01:01:20.180 --> 01:01:25.420
[Guest]: is kind of disengaging from the subcontinent a little bit.

01:01:25.420 --> 01:01:29.820
[Guest]: Under Lyndon Johnson, the United States is increasingly involved in the war in Vietnam.

01:01:29.820 --> 01:01:34.220
[Guest]: During the 1965 war between India and Pakistan, the Americans kind of take more or less what

01:01:34.220 --> 01:01:37.260
[Guest]: I call a plague on both your houses kind of attitude, right?

01:01:37.260 --> 01:01:41.060
[Guest]: They impose arms embargoes on both sides, they say we're not going to give any aid and

01:01:41.060 --> 01:01:42.060
[Guest]: so on.

01:01:42.060 --> 01:01:45.340
[Guest]: And ultimately, when the post war conference is held, it is held by the Soviet Union.

01:01:45.340 --> 01:01:48.140
[Guest]: It's in Tashkent, that's where Lal Bahadur Shastri dies, right?

01:01:48.140 --> 01:01:51.420
[Guest]: So it's a very interesting thing that for the first time, the United States actually

01:01:51.420 --> 01:01:55.860
[Guest]: allows the Soviet Union to take the lead in settling the geopolitical affairs of the subcontinent.

01:01:55.860 --> 01:01:56.860
[Guest]: Why is this?

01:01:56.860 --> 01:01:57.860
[Guest]: Because of American involvement in Vietnam.

01:01:57.860 --> 01:01:58.860
[Guest]: Right.

01:01:58.860 --> 01:02:03.180
[Guest]: Johnson just decides that, listen, these are incorrigible countries, you know, let the

01:02:03.180 --> 01:02:05.920
[Guest]: Soviets go and break their head against that wall if they want to, you know, he has to

01:02:05.920 --> 01:02:09.460
[Guest]: worry about great society at home, he has to worry about Vietnam abroad, right?

01:02:09.460 --> 01:02:10.700
[Guest]: So his priorities are pretty full.

01:02:10.700 --> 01:02:14.180
[Guest]: And that's, you know, the Civil Rights Bill is being sort of activated at the time.

01:02:14.180 --> 01:02:16.860
[Guest]: So lots of things happening.

01:02:16.860 --> 01:02:18.620
[Guest]: So there's a period of kind of disengagement.

01:02:18.620 --> 01:02:21.820
[Guest]: But then once you have the Nixon administration come in, they come in with a very different

01:02:21.820 --> 01:02:26.460
[Guest]: set of priorities, which is to say that they want to get out of Vietnam, but get out in

01:02:26.460 --> 01:02:27.540
[Guest]: an honorable fashion, right?

01:02:27.540 --> 01:02:33.100
[Guest]: So an American exit has to be sort of orchestrated in such a way that it does not seem as a scoot

01:02:33.100 --> 01:02:34.340
[Guest]: and run.

01:02:34.340 --> 01:02:38.140
[Guest]: And in that context, they believe that the United States will need to sort of reach out

01:02:38.140 --> 01:02:43.260
[Guest]: to China, which is seen as a country which will allow them to sort of, you know, influence

01:02:43.260 --> 01:02:46.440
[Guest]: North Vietnam to the negotiating table and such like things.

01:02:46.440 --> 01:02:50.100
[Guest]: In order to reach to China, the Americans decide to sort of go through Pakistan because

01:02:50.100 --> 01:02:54.740
[Guest]: Pakistan and China have a good relationship going back to 1962-63 when India and China

01:02:54.740 --> 01:02:56.260
[Guest]: have fought, right?

01:02:56.260 --> 01:03:01.780
[Guest]: So Yahya Khan, who's the new military dictator of Pakistan, actually acts as a conduit between

01:03:01.780 --> 01:03:05.020
[Guest]: the Nixon administration and the Chinese leadership.

01:03:05.020 --> 01:03:10.820
[Guest]: And in that context, the Pakistanis and the Yahya Khan regime acquires an importance in

01:03:10.820 --> 01:03:13.740
[Guest]: the Nixon administration's mind, which is kind of out of proportion to anything the

01:03:13.740 --> 01:03:17.060
[Guest]: Pakistanis were doing at that point of time, partly because Americans were doing it, the

01:03:17.060 --> 01:03:19.060
[Guest]: Nixon administration was doing it so secretively.

01:03:19.060 --> 01:03:23.980
[Guest]: I mean, Nixon did not even inform his own sort of senior cabinet officials about this

01:03:23.980 --> 01:03:24.980
[Guest]: stuff, right?

01:03:24.980 --> 01:03:26.460
[Guest]: It was all done in a hush-hush way.

01:03:26.460 --> 01:03:29.940
[Guest]: And because of this extreme drive towards secrecy and need to sort of keep especially

01:03:29.940 --> 01:03:33.020
[Guest]: congressional Republicans out of the frame, because you're reaching out to China, the

01:03:33.020 --> 01:03:34.020
[Guest]: old enemy, right?

01:03:34.020 --> 01:03:38.980
[Guest]: They want to do it completely through a secret channel and Pakistan becomes important.

01:03:38.980 --> 01:03:43.380
[Guest]: But this opening up to Pakistan and Kissinger visits Pakistan in summer of 1971.

01:03:43.380 --> 01:03:45.460
[Guest]: And after that, it's out in the open.

01:03:45.460 --> 01:03:47.980
[Guest]: That coincides, of course, with the onset of the Bangladesh crisis, which has begun

01:03:47.980 --> 01:03:52.380
[Guest]: with the crackdown of the Pakistan army on the Bengalis in March.

01:03:52.380 --> 01:03:58.300
[Guest]: By the end of summer 1971, you have an estimated 10 million refugees on Indian soil.

01:03:58.300 --> 01:04:01.860
[Guest]: And it is quite clear that this is an issue which is, you know, definitely going to escalate

01:04:01.860 --> 01:04:02.860
[Guest]: very soon.

01:04:02.860 --> 01:04:07.020
[Guest]: And the Americans at that point of time, take a very pro-Pakistan line.

01:04:07.020 --> 01:04:11.700
[Guest]: In a sense, it is arguable about whether the United States actually needed to do that in

01:04:11.700 --> 01:04:14.460
[Guest]: order to pursue even its own hard-nosed interests with China.

01:04:14.460 --> 01:04:18.660
[Guest]: Because what we know from Chinese sources and other things is that the Chinese themselves

01:04:18.660 --> 01:04:22.140
[Guest]: were telling the Pakistanis to sort of back away from that kind of an extreme military

01:04:22.140 --> 01:04:23.900
[Guest]: action against the Bengalis.

01:04:23.900 --> 01:04:25.720
[Guest]: But the Americans wouldn't want to do it.

01:04:25.720 --> 01:04:29.340
[Guest]: And finally, when the war happened, the United States took a very antagonistic position towards

01:04:29.340 --> 01:04:30.340
[Guest]: India.

01:04:30.340 --> 01:04:31.660
[Guest]: They cut off all economic aid to India.

01:04:31.660 --> 01:04:35.100
[Guest]: They cut off all military aid to India, of course, even earlier.

01:04:35.100 --> 01:04:40.500
[Guest]: And then they sent the sort of, you know, the 7th Fleet with, you know, aircraft carrier

01:04:40.500 --> 01:04:45.940
[Guest]: with nuclear weapons on board to the Bay of Bengal in an attempt to intimidate the Indians.

01:04:45.940 --> 01:04:49.620
[Guest]: And of course, the Americans claim that Nixon Kissinger believed, you know, or whatever,

01:04:49.620 --> 01:04:52.860
[Guest]: they used it as a pretext that the Indians were going to attack West Pakistan and not

01:04:52.860 --> 01:04:53.860
[Guest]: just East and so on.

01:04:53.860 --> 01:04:59.140
[Guest]: So whatever be the reasons, the reality was that that episode really sort of ends up marking

01:04:59.140 --> 01:05:01.100
[Amit Varma]: a deep rupture in US India relations.

01:05:01.100 --> 01:05:04.620
[Amit Varma]: And the Indians just had moved into Dhaka before really anything much happened.

01:05:04.620 --> 01:05:05.620
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:05:05.620 --> 01:05:09.860
[Guest]: So in a sense, I mean, nothing happened in a real sense, but it left behind a legacy,

01:05:09.860 --> 01:05:14.020
[Guest]: which was, you know, which was very difficult to sort of pick up pieces.

01:05:14.020 --> 01:05:17.900
[Guest]: And also for Pakistan, because Pakistanis believe that Americans actually did not help

01:05:17.900 --> 01:05:19.740
[Guest]: them very much during this, right.

01:05:19.740 --> 01:05:23.580
[Guest]: So, so, so you again have a period of disengagement with Pakistan, US Pakistan relations, US India

01:05:23.580 --> 01:05:26.020
[Guest]: relations are very turbulent.

01:05:26.020 --> 01:05:30.300
[Guest]: And one sort of knock on consequence of the 1971 thing, which in some ways goes to your

01:05:30.300 --> 01:05:35.300
[Guest]: point, which is the recalibration of American sort of priorities in the subcontinent in

01:05:35.300 --> 01:05:41.780
[Guest]: the mid 1970s, was the Indian decision to test nuclear weapons, which was at least given

01:05:41.780 --> 01:05:46.580
[Guest]: a certain impetus by the 1971 crisis and what happened during that time.

01:05:46.580 --> 01:05:52.460
[Guest]: And you know, in 1974, India goes nuclear and preventing India from, you know, becoming

01:05:52.460 --> 01:05:55.740
[Guest]: a proliferator is a very important American priority from there on.

01:05:55.740 --> 01:06:00.580
[Guest]: So nuclear weapons as a whole and subcontinent, it's worth pointing out that the Pakistanis

01:06:00.580 --> 01:06:05.700
[Guest]: were already thinking about starting a nuclear program by 1972, soon after their country

01:06:05.700 --> 01:06:06.700
[Guest]: had been divided.

01:06:06.700 --> 01:06:09.900
[Guest]: So it's not as if they started only after the Indian tests, but the Indian tests again

01:06:09.900 --> 01:06:12.700
[Guest]: given impetus to the Pakistani program.

01:06:12.700 --> 01:06:17.540
[Guest]: The second thing which happens in the 1970s, which I think, again, marks a complete break

01:06:17.540 --> 01:06:22.060
[Guest]: from the old Cold War priorities is the rise of what you might refer to as political Islam

01:06:22.060 --> 01:06:26.500
[Guest]: or Islamism in Pakistan with the advent of Zia ul Haq.

01:06:26.500 --> 01:06:31.620
[Guest]: But even before that, with Pakistani support to groups like the Jamaat-e-Islami of Afghanistan,

01:06:31.620 --> 01:06:36.460
[Guest]: which the Pakistanis were using in order to basically keep the Afghan regime from making

01:06:36.460 --> 01:06:38.500
[Guest]: claims on Pashtunistan, right?

01:06:38.500 --> 01:06:43.900
[Guest]: And now once the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan happens in 1979, the whole dimension of using

01:06:43.900 --> 01:06:48.420
[Guest]: the Islamist fighters, they call them freedom fighters, Mujahideen, to drive the Soviet

01:06:48.420 --> 01:06:53.580
[Guest]: Union out becomes a major priority for the United States, both the last parts of the

01:06:53.580 --> 01:06:58.100
[Guest]: Carter administration and the Reagan administration, a lot of effort is spent in the subcontinent

01:06:58.100 --> 01:07:00.340
[Guest]: on doing this.

01:07:00.340 --> 01:07:04.660
[Guest]: But that also means that you're also turning a blind eye to Pakistani sort of efforts at

01:07:04.660 --> 01:07:08.100
[Guest]: acquiring their own nuclear weapon, which the Americans know very well about, right?

01:07:08.100 --> 01:07:12.660
[Guest]: And we now know from declassified American documents, which I've used in reconstructing

01:07:12.660 --> 01:07:18.620
[Guest]: that particular part of the story, that the Americans confronted Zia ul Haq about his

01:07:18.620 --> 01:07:22.060
[Guest]: nuclear programs with evidence, you know, which obviously they had collected through

01:07:22.060 --> 01:07:26.700
[Guest]: technical and other intelligence sources and allowed Zia to sort of get away with evasive

01:07:26.700 --> 01:07:31.260
[Guest]: lies and not just that, but gave congressional certification under the Reagan administration

01:07:31.260 --> 01:07:34.380
[Guest]: successively saying that the Pakistanis are not pursuing a bomb, right?

01:07:34.380 --> 01:07:41.180
[Guest]: So in a sense, the period between 1975 and 87, 88, in many ways, you encounter a set

01:07:41.180 --> 01:07:45.060
[Guest]: of problems, which I think mark the major concerns for the Americans today.

01:07:45.060 --> 01:07:49.100
[Guest]: If the Americans today believe that the subcontinent, or at least they've sort of said that is the

01:07:49.100 --> 01:07:54.500
[Guest]: most dangerous place, it is because of this confluence of nuclear weapons and, you know,

01:07:54.500 --> 01:07:59.820
[Guest]: these jihadi forces, which ultimately are the sort of ultimate nightmare of every American

01:07:59.820 --> 01:08:01.460
[Guest]: administration when it comes to subcontinent.

01:08:01.460 --> 01:08:05.700
[Guest]: That somehow, you know, one of these guys is going to get hold of one of those devices

01:08:05.700 --> 01:08:07.620
[Guest]: or materials and so on.

01:08:07.620 --> 01:08:10.300
[Guest]: And but the problem goes back to the mid seventies.

01:08:10.300 --> 01:08:13.820
[Guest]: And so which is why I say that in some ways, you know, from the mid seventies, it's not

01:08:13.820 --> 01:08:17.420
[Guest]: just the old Cold War priorities of saying we need Pakistan to contain the Soviet Union

01:08:17.420 --> 01:08:20.900
[Amit Varma]: and so on, but a completely new set of issues which comes to the fore.

01:08:20.900 --> 01:08:21.900
[Amit Varma]: And so here's my question.

01:08:21.900 --> 01:08:27.300
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the US then takes a bunch of decisions around supporting Islamism and around backing

01:08:27.300 --> 01:08:32.420
[Amit Varma]: Zia, funding the ISI, backing the Mujahideen and so on and so forth, which have grave historical

01:08:32.420 --> 01:08:34.620
[Amit Varma]: consequences a couple of decades onwards.

01:08:34.620 --> 01:08:38.300
[Amit Varma]: But at that time, strategically must have seemed completely reasonable and the only

01:08:38.300 --> 01:08:39.300
[Amit Varma]: thing to do.

01:08:39.300 --> 01:08:41.260
[Amit Varma]: I mean, what are the counterfactuals here?

01:08:41.260 --> 01:08:42.940
[Amit Varma]: Could they have done anything differently?

01:08:42.940 --> 01:08:47.500
[Amit Varma]: Like, is it fair to now point a finger and say that, hey, you know, you created Osama?

01:08:47.500 --> 01:08:51.940
[Amit Varma]: Or was there something at the time they could have done differently without the benefit

01:08:51.940 --> 01:08:52.940
[Guest]: of hindsight?

01:08:52.940 --> 01:08:56.860
[Guest]: Well, I mean, so I think it's fair to say that, you know, the Americans did not create

01:08:56.860 --> 01:09:00.180
[Guest]: Osama in any straightforward sense of the word, right?

01:09:00.180 --> 01:09:07.460
[Guest]: But the reality is that the United States supported a group of people, you know, various

01:09:07.460 --> 01:09:15.780
[Guest]: kinds of Islamist guerrillas and allowed Pakistan to build a sort of an infrastructure to support

01:09:15.780 --> 01:09:21.580
[Guest]: and utilize these groups, over which Americans had very little oversight and basically got

01:09:21.580 --> 01:09:24.420
[Guest]: the Saudis to match their contributions all in the name of doing this.

01:09:24.420 --> 01:09:29.940
[Guest]: And actually, towards the far end of it, ended up giving very dangerous systems to the Mujahideen,

01:09:29.940 --> 01:09:33.500
[Guest]: including the infamous Stinger missiles, you know, which they were bringing down sort of

01:09:33.500 --> 01:09:35.980
[Guest]: surface to air missiles, handheld surface to air missiles.

01:09:35.980 --> 01:09:39.100
[Guest]: And the Americans spent the better part of the late 1980s actually trying to buy those

01:09:39.100 --> 01:09:41.980
[Guest]: from black markets all over the world, right?

01:09:41.980 --> 01:09:43.340
[Guest]: So those are very counterproductive things.

01:09:43.340 --> 01:09:49.100
[Guest]: So in a sense, while, you know, their desire to sort of get the Soviets out of Afghanistan

01:09:49.100 --> 01:09:53.300
[Guest]: might have been understandable, you know, it's not clear to me that this was necessarily

01:09:53.300 --> 01:09:54.700
[Guest]: the best way of doing it.

01:09:54.700 --> 01:09:58.460
[Guest]: And what is interesting is that the problems with these approaches were pointed out to

01:09:58.460 --> 01:09:59.460
[Guest]: them at that point of time.

01:09:59.460 --> 01:10:03.060
[Guest]: It's not that we are talking about this stuff with a post 9-11 kind of view, right?

01:10:03.060 --> 01:10:08.220
[Guest]: I mean, if you look at the records of conversation, we now have a few of them between Rajiv Gandhi

01:10:08.220 --> 01:10:11.100
[Guest]: and officials in the Reagan administration.

01:10:11.100 --> 01:10:14.380
[Guest]: The Indians are constantly pointing out, you know, it's actually quite, it is almost a

01:10:14.380 --> 01:10:18.900
[Guest]: replay of what is happening in the mid 2000s, where, you know, the Indians are constantly

01:10:18.900 --> 01:10:21.540
[Guest]: pointing out to them saying that, listen, look at the kind of people you're supporting,

01:10:21.540 --> 01:10:25.900
[Guest]: Gulbuddin, Hikmatyar, I mean, people like them are genuinely extremists.

01:10:25.900 --> 01:10:30.780
[Guest]: And that if you are going to give, allow these groups to sort of come to power in Afghanistan,

01:10:30.780 --> 01:10:33.580
[Guest]: it is going to lead to a great degree of instability in the region and we are not just saying it

01:10:33.580 --> 01:10:36.540
[Guest]: for ourselves, but on the whole, right?

01:10:36.540 --> 01:10:41.320
[Guest]: I mean, in that sense, and of course, as I said, I mean, not just the sort of allowing

01:10:41.320 --> 01:10:44.500
[Guest]: these groups to sort of take place, but allowing Pakistan to sort of develop a nuclear weapons

01:10:44.500 --> 01:10:50.100
[Guest]: program covertly and assisting them in effect, you know, by sort of allowing them to do this

01:10:50.100 --> 01:10:52.340
[Guest]: stuff was a deadly cocktail.

01:10:52.340 --> 01:10:55.940
[Guest]: And again, I don't think these are only criticisms which can be made with the benefit of hindsight.

01:10:55.940 --> 01:11:00.660
[Guest]: I think people are pointing it out at that point of time, that these were dangerous policies.

01:11:00.660 --> 01:11:06.180
[Guest]: And that the acquisition of nuclear weapons by Pakistan in such a covert manner would

01:11:06.180 --> 01:11:09.620
[Guest]: have very destabilizing consequences or support for these kinds of groups.

01:11:09.620 --> 01:11:12.900
[Guest]: Of course, someone like Osama bin Laden was in the play even then, but I don't think I

01:11:12.900 --> 01:11:16.140
[Guest]: think it's fair to say that he was not a very important player.

01:11:16.140 --> 01:11:17.140
[Guest]: But nevertheless, that was a milieu.

01:11:17.140 --> 01:11:19.580
[Amit Varma]: I mean, that was an unintended consequence, obviously.

01:11:19.580 --> 01:11:23.460
[Guest]: I mean, I think, I mean, what was unforeseeable at that point of time was that, you know,

01:11:23.460 --> 01:11:27.540
[Guest]: some of these people would then target America much later, but then you had to have a series

01:11:27.540 --> 01:11:28.540
[Guest]: of intervening events, right?

01:11:28.540 --> 01:11:32.780
[Guest]: I mean, you have to have the American sort of participation in the Gulf War, their presence

01:11:32.780 --> 01:11:37.260
[Guest]: in Saudi Arabia, which then led Osama to sort of, you know, think of Americans as the sort

01:11:37.260 --> 01:11:38.780
[Amit Varma]: of most important enemy and so on.

01:11:38.780 --> 01:11:41.580
[Guest]: It's that perfect storm of events, if we may call it that.

01:11:41.580 --> 01:11:43.580
[Guest]: So, I mean, that is subsequent history.

01:11:43.580 --> 01:11:47.300
[Guest]: I mean, I think we should not be anachronistic by reading later events into that point of

01:11:47.300 --> 01:11:48.300
[Guest]: time.

01:11:48.300 --> 01:11:52.460
[Guest]: But at that point of time, you know, even the characters with whom the Americans dealt,

01:11:52.460 --> 01:11:54.260
[Guest]: many of whom those dramatic person are still around.

01:11:54.260 --> 01:11:58.540
[Guest]: I mean, you know, just earlier this year, we had Gulbuddin Hekmatyar walking back into

01:11:58.540 --> 01:12:02.660
[Guest]: Kabul, which for people who live through their generation was an extraordinary sort of event,

01:12:02.660 --> 01:12:07.660
[Guest]: because this man kind of was single-handedly responsible for the destruction of Kabul by

01:12:07.660 --> 01:12:10.660
[Guest]: artillery firing, you know, in the early 90s.

01:12:10.660 --> 01:12:14.220
[Guest]: And these are people with some very, very unsavory past.

01:12:14.220 --> 01:12:18.940
[Amit Varma]: So, so while, you know, this whole conflict is kind of blowing up and, you know, this

01:12:18.940 --> 01:12:23.100
[Amit Varma]: is almost like a new front or a new narrative in the old front.

01:12:23.100 --> 01:12:27.940
[Amit Varma]: Even old story comes to an end, the Cold War ends very abruptly when the Soviet Union collapses.

01:12:27.940 --> 01:12:31.740
[Amit Varma]: And shortly after that, you have India's liberalization.

01:12:31.740 --> 01:12:33.820
[Amit Varma]: And you know, these have dual consequences.

01:12:33.820 --> 01:12:37.380
[Amit Varma]: One of course is that the Cold War imperatives no longer really matter.

01:12:37.380 --> 01:12:42.660
[Amit Varma]: And the other is that the ideological tension between the US and India now seems to be coming

01:12:42.660 --> 01:12:45.060
[Amit Varma]: to an end because India has opened up.

01:12:45.060 --> 01:12:48.820
[Amit Varma]: And the third consequence of this is that the third strand apart from power and ideology,

01:12:48.820 --> 01:12:53.780
[Amit Varma]: which you speak of is culture, and American culture, which was already popular in India,

01:12:53.780 --> 01:12:56.780
[Amit Varma]: but now essentially enters and takes over young India.

01:12:56.780 --> 01:12:58.220
[Guest]: Yeah, I think absolutely.

01:12:58.220 --> 01:13:04.420
[Guest]: So I, you know, and I think you have to bring each of these various strands into the frame

01:13:04.420 --> 01:13:08.380
[Guest]: to quite understand why US India relations have really transformed in the post Cold War

01:13:08.380 --> 01:13:09.380
[Guest]: period, right?

01:13:09.380 --> 01:13:14.820
[Guest]: I mean, why is it that two countries which were sort of divided on sort of political,

01:13:14.820 --> 01:13:18.860
[Guest]: economic grounds had these cultural gaps, which as we've discussed now, you know, quite

01:13:18.860 --> 01:13:23.980
[Guest]: sort of important, persistent, and so on, managed to actually come together in that

01:13:23.980 --> 01:13:24.980
[Guest]: period.

01:13:24.980 --> 01:13:27.740
[Guest]: And I think the answer to that is not just the end of the Cold War, because in some ways,

01:13:27.740 --> 01:13:31.340
[Guest]: US India relations were already improving even before the Cold War ended, right?

01:13:31.340 --> 01:13:35.900
[Guest]: I mean, and, you know, the declassified documents that we now have access to, I think suggests

01:13:35.900 --> 01:13:39.900
[Guest]: that Rajiv Gandhi in some ways was the most pro American Prime Minister that you had in

01:13:39.900 --> 01:13:42.620
[Guest]: independent India up to that point of time.

01:13:42.620 --> 01:13:46.980
[Guest]: He understood that, you know, for whatever big visions that he had for India as a sort

01:13:46.980 --> 01:13:50.580
[Guest]: of 21st century country, which needed to get into computers and all of that stuff, some

01:13:50.580 --> 01:13:52.980
[Guest]: sort of story of modernization.

01:13:52.980 --> 01:13:55.380
[Guest]: The United States was going to be very important.

01:13:55.380 --> 01:13:59.780
[Guest]: And Rajiv Gandhi was, you know, tried very hard to develop good relations with the Reagan

01:13:59.780 --> 01:14:03.780
[Guest]: administration, you know, to get all of this high technology transfer, of course, there

01:14:03.780 --> 01:14:07.140
[Guest]: were issues still over a range of things.

01:14:07.140 --> 01:14:10.780
[Guest]: But you know, you again understood that once the Soviet Union was going through whatever

01:14:10.780 --> 01:14:15.900
[Guest]: glassnost, perestroika, etc, under Gorbachev, that the old Cold War dimensions were no longer

01:14:15.900 --> 01:14:16.900
[Guest]: going to play.

01:14:16.900 --> 01:14:19.900
[Guest]: So in a sense, tilt towards the United States starts happening even before the Soviet Union

01:14:19.900 --> 01:14:20.900
[Unknown]: starts.

01:14:20.900 --> 01:14:22.580
[Guest]: Of course, it's accelerated completely by the collapse of the Soviet Union, because

01:14:22.580 --> 01:14:25.220
[Guest]: that takes away a complete anchor of global politics, right?

01:14:25.220 --> 01:14:28.420
[Guest]: I mean, so it's a dramatic change not to minimize its impact.

01:14:28.420 --> 01:14:30.540
[Guest]: But some of the shift was already happening, right?

01:14:30.540 --> 01:14:33.100
[Guest]: The second, of course, was, as you're saying, you know, something which is actually a bit

01:14:33.100 --> 01:14:36.980
[Guest]: of a coincidence, which is the sort of the whatever, you know, the sort of balance of

01:14:36.980 --> 01:14:41.580
[Guest]: payment crisis, which again, you know, it could have happened anytime during the Adi

01:14:41.580 --> 01:14:44.900
[Guest]: Gandhi's period, because in some ways, it is actually, you know, again, that's where

01:14:44.900 --> 01:14:47.260
[Guest]: the law of unintended consequences, right?

01:14:47.260 --> 01:14:54.100
[Guest]: One of the reasons, one of the sort of advantages of going closer to the United States during

01:14:54.100 --> 01:14:57.980
[Guest]: this period for the Indians also was that you wanted access to capital markets for external

01:14:57.980 --> 01:14:59.620
[Guest]: commercial borrowing.

01:14:59.620 --> 01:15:03.460
[Guest]: And the Americans are happy to sort of because they don't want to sort of do economic aid

01:15:03.460 --> 01:15:06.180
[Guest]: for India, they see India as a much bigger economy, there's no economic aid, but you

01:15:06.180 --> 01:15:08.300
[Guest]: can borrow in the markets and stuff.

01:15:08.300 --> 01:15:13.820
[Guest]: And once Indian borrowing on Western American sort of Wall Street and other places starts

01:15:13.820 --> 01:15:18.060
[Guest]: picking up, that is when you know, the problems for your later period are being stored up,

01:15:18.060 --> 01:15:19.060
[Guest]: right?

01:15:19.060 --> 01:15:20.860
[Guest]: I mean, and that's, that's where the crisis comes, actually.

01:15:20.860 --> 01:15:24.740
[Guest]: So in a sense, but it's an independent development.

01:15:24.740 --> 01:15:27.260
[Guest]: And then your back is up against the wall, you have to sort of reform.

01:15:27.260 --> 01:15:33.380
[Guest]: And for the first time, at least since the 1930s, India is accepts that, you know, embrace

01:15:33.380 --> 01:15:36.340
[Guest]: of globalization is a good thing for us.

01:15:36.340 --> 01:15:39.900
[Guest]: And that I think is an important, not just from an ideological point of view, but from

01:15:39.900 --> 01:15:41.780
[Guest]: practical American perspective, right?

01:15:41.780 --> 01:15:46.700
[Guest]: Because what you had was, you know, this kind of closed economy or with limited access to

01:15:46.700 --> 01:15:50.420
[Guest]: the external world, where aid is the main driver of relationship, etc.

01:15:50.420 --> 01:15:52.740
[Guest]: Inhibited certain forms of things that Americans want, right?

01:15:52.740 --> 01:15:57.320
[Guest]: So in that sense, the, but the opening up of the Indian economy also had other kinds

01:15:57.320 --> 01:16:02.300
[Guest]: of cultural consequences, because the Americans were now able to bring to the subcontinent

01:16:02.300 --> 01:16:06.300
[Guest]: what other historians of Europe have called, you know, the commercial imperium, so to speak,

01:16:06.300 --> 01:16:07.300
[Guest]: right?

01:16:07.300 --> 01:16:10.420
[Guest]: The Emporium as the Imperium, as one of them puts it, right, which is to say that, you

01:16:10.420 --> 01:16:15.060
[Guest]: know, in a sense, that is a very important part of America's allure and its leadership

01:16:15.060 --> 01:16:21.300
[Guest]: in the 20th century is the extraordinary sort of cultural impact that American, you know,

01:16:21.300 --> 01:16:25.180
[Guest]: sort of commercial practices and models have persisted.

01:16:25.180 --> 01:16:28.100
[Guest]: And you, of course, would remember when MTV came to India, right?

01:16:28.100 --> 01:16:30.100
[Unknown]: I mean, what was there?

01:16:30.100 --> 01:16:33.340
[Guest]: So, you know, for people of our generation, I suppose we've lived through some of these

01:16:33.340 --> 01:16:34.340
[Guest]: changes.

01:16:34.340 --> 01:16:37.180
[Guest]: So, and they were very striking changes.

01:16:37.180 --> 01:16:42.860
[Guest]: And I think what a current generation, younger generation of Indians takes for granted was

01:16:42.860 --> 01:16:45.540
[Guest]: a transformation that, you know, people like us live through.

01:16:45.540 --> 01:16:48.700
[Amit Varma]: And I think we often take like American cultural power for granted.

01:16:48.700 --> 01:16:51.900
[Amit Varma]: Like I watched a talk of yours on YouTube, which you gave at Goa.

01:16:51.900 --> 01:16:56.620
[Amit Varma]: And one of your fellow panelists, Professor Varun Sani, made a very interesting point

01:16:56.620 --> 01:17:00.700
[Amit Varma]: that if you just look at how culture permeates across the world and the differences between

01:17:00.700 --> 01:17:04.740
[Amit Varma]: American culture and other cultures, is that anybody can wear a sari, but a sari would

01:17:04.740 --> 01:17:06.940
[Amit Varma]: look like fancy dress on a foreigner.

01:17:06.940 --> 01:17:10.820
[Amit Varma]: But anybody can wear blue jeans and completely it just seems natural.

01:17:10.820 --> 01:17:15.580
[Amit Varma]: And we are all in a sense, even old fogies like us who are in our 40s, but even we are

01:17:15.580 --> 01:17:20.460
[Amit Varma]: like far more American, culturally, than we realize otherwise.

01:17:20.460 --> 01:17:21.460
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:17:21.460 --> 01:17:27.140
[Guest]: So, I think that the important shift which happens in the 90s, right, is that, you know,

01:17:27.140 --> 01:17:31.300
[Guest]: because the India in which people of our age sort of grew up, right?

01:17:31.300 --> 01:17:35.260
[Guest]: I mean, the way I think about it, you know, there was a culture of conspicuous non consumption,

01:17:35.260 --> 01:17:36.260
[Unknown]: right?

01:17:36.260 --> 01:17:38.340
[Guest]: You know, the Indian elites almost would go out of their way to say that, listen, we are

01:17:38.340 --> 01:17:41.300
[Guest]: wearing khadi and that, you know, you don't want to sort of this thing, there's no alcohol

01:17:41.300 --> 01:17:43.540
[Guest]: permitted in official functions, etc, etc, right?

01:17:43.540 --> 01:17:47.200
[Guest]: I mean, the whole gamut of, you know, there is a very self conscious sense that you want

01:17:47.200 --> 01:17:49.900
[Guest]: to sort of have this non consumption attitude, right?

01:17:49.900 --> 01:17:51.780
[Guest]: Which changes, which changes quite dramatically.

01:17:51.780 --> 01:17:54.100
[Guest]: And that allows them for a range of things.

01:17:54.100 --> 01:17:58.060
[Guest]: And I think, you know, what Varun Sani was saying there, and which I would put it in

01:17:58.060 --> 01:18:02.020
[Guest]: slightly different ways, but I think the point remains the same, which is that, you know,

01:18:02.020 --> 01:18:06.620
[Guest]: people tend to sort of criticize, especially, you know, Europeans, especially Europeans

01:18:06.620 --> 01:18:10.260
[Guest]: of early 20th century, when American commercial culture first landed up in Europe after the

01:18:10.260 --> 01:18:11.780
[Guest]: First World War.

01:18:11.780 --> 01:18:15.180
[Guest]: The European old elite used to sort of snigger at American culture and say, listen, how can

01:18:15.180 --> 01:18:16.180
[Guest]: you call this stuff culture, right?

01:18:16.180 --> 01:18:19.860
[Guest]: I mean, culture is what we had, Bildung is what Germans had, you know, we had this, you

01:18:19.860 --> 01:18:23.340
[Guest]: know, this whole sort of heritage of high culture of the West.

01:18:23.340 --> 01:18:29.180
[Guest]: But the reality is that American popular culture is attractive precisely because it's shallow.

01:18:29.180 --> 01:18:32.620
[Guest]: It is its very shallowness that allows it to sort of inhabit various domains, right?

01:18:32.620 --> 01:18:37.340
[Guest]: So for one of the things I talk about in this book, which again, is kind of, you know, people

01:18:37.340 --> 01:18:41.380
[Guest]: like as a witness to our lives, is the establishment of McDonald's chains in this country, right?

01:18:41.380 --> 01:18:44.540
[Guest]: How a brand like McDonald's has adapted itself to the Indian market, right?

01:18:44.540 --> 01:18:48.580
[Guest]: I mean, I've just come from a week in Japan, you can't get the stuff that you get in McDonald's

01:18:48.580 --> 01:18:51.300
[Guest]: here in any McDonald's in Japan, right?

01:18:51.300 --> 01:18:54.060
[Guest]: And then the stuff that they give in McDonald's in Japan, I've not even eaten McDonald's in

01:18:54.060 --> 01:18:55.060
[Guest]: the United States, right?

01:18:55.060 --> 01:19:01.300
[Guest]: So, so the ability to sort of nestle into various cultural contexts is there primarily

01:19:01.300 --> 01:19:06.180
[Guest]: because of this quality that we tend to dismiss as shallow, or as you know, easy to adapt,

01:19:06.180 --> 01:19:07.460
[Guest]: but that adaptability is what counts, right?

01:19:07.460 --> 01:19:10.420
[Guest]: I mean, how many people are going to take the pains to watch Chinese opera?

01:19:10.420 --> 01:19:14.220
[Guest]: And what do you think are the odds that China will be able to sort of exercise the same

01:19:14.220 --> 01:19:15.220
[Guest]: degree of cultural influence?

01:19:15.220 --> 01:19:16.220
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:19:16.220 --> 01:19:18.700
[Amit Varma]: Because Chinese language is much harder to learn and so on.

01:19:18.700 --> 01:19:19.700
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:19:19.700 --> 01:19:24.220
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, you know, Francis Fukuyama once prematurely spoke of the end of history.

01:19:24.220 --> 01:19:29.180
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, it would seem that in the 90s, you also have an end to the conflict

01:19:29.180 --> 01:19:33.580
[Amit Varma]: between the US and India, because on all three fronts, you know, the power front, the Cold

01:19:33.580 --> 01:19:37.060
[Amit Varma]: War is over, it no longer matters, India is no longer a Soviet ally.

01:19:37.060 --> 01:19:40.660
[Amit Varma]: In the ideological front, India's becoming a capitalist economy.

01:19:40.660 --> 01:19:43.580
[Amit Varma]: On the cultural front, America is basically taking over.

01:19:43.580 --> 01:19:47.460
[Amit Varma]: And you think that everything's going to be hunky dory from now, but of course, you know,

01:19:47.460 --> 01:19:48.900
[Amit Varma]: Fukuyama was premature.

01:19:48.900 --> 01:19:54.140
[Amit Varma]: And even in the context of India US relations, everything changes with 9-11.

01:19:54.140 --> 01:19:57.020
[Guest]: Yes, things do change with 9-11.

01:19:57.020 --> 01:20:01.980
[Guest]: But, but again, I think from a longer historical perspective, you know, the change doesn't

01:20:01.980 --> 01:20:05.660
[Guest]: seem as marked as it seemed to us at that point of time.

01:20:05.660 --> 01:20:09.300
[Guest]: Let me say this both with respect to India Pakistan relations, but also Pakistan, Afghanistan,

01:20:09.300 --> 01:20:10.300
[Guest]: right.

01:20:10.300 --> 01:20:15.860
[Guest]: So from the Pakistan Afghanistan thing, what is interesting is 9-11 once again, reaffirms

01:20:15.860 --> 01:20:19.860
[Guest]: a sort of a pattern of cyclical engagement, disengagement between Pakistan and China,

01:20:19.860 --> 01:20:20.860
[Guest]: right.

01:20:20.860 --> 01:20:26.060
[Guest]: In the mid 1950s, Pakistan and China come together, Pakistan and America come together.

01:20:26.060 --> 01:20:28.860
[Guest]: In the 1960s, it's a bit of a turn back.

01:20:28.860 --> 01:20:33.380
[Guest]: In the early 70s, again, they sort of together, late 70s and early 80s, they're together again

01:20:33.380 --> 01:20:34.380
[Guest]: in Afghanistan.

01:20:34.380 --> 01:20:38.380
[Guest]: So you have that sort of cyclical disengagement, reengagement happening.

01:20:38.380 --> 01:20:41.460
[Guest]: And that is primarily because of Pakistan's geopolitical location more than anything else.

01:20:41.460 --> 01:20:44.740
[Guest]: So in a sense, if Pakistan has an advantage, it's actually geography.

01:20:44.740 --> 01:20:50.020
[Guest]: And it sits strides areas, which are quite difficult for anybody else to access and has

01:20:50.020 --> 01:20:54.740
[Guest]: a certain vantage point, because of its peculiar geography, which, you know, gives us certain

01:20:54.740 --> 01:20:55.740
[Guest]: kinds of advantages.

01:20:55.740 --> 01:20:58.900
[Guest]: And that's what you know, colleagues like Nitin Pai say that, you know, it's geopolitical

01:20:58.900 --> 01:20:59.900
[Guest]: rent, right.

01:20:59.900 --> 01:21:01.740
[Guest]: I mean, in some ways, that's exactly what it is a geographic rent, actually.

01:21:01.740 --> 01:21:04.460
[Guest]: I mean, in geopolitics comes fundamentally from your geography, right.

01:21:04.460 --> 01:21:06.780
[Guest]: So that is a huge advantage.

01:21:06.780 --> 01:21:10.480
[Guest]: In the context of US India relations, of course, you know, it's a, it's a very different kind

01:21:10.480 --> 01:21:11.480
[Guest]: of reaction, right?

01:21:11.480 --> 01:21:16.180
[Guest]: Because what happens post 9-11 is that certain forms of activity that the Americans might

01:21:16.180 --> 01:21:19.820
[Guest]: have sort of put up with through the 90s, in the name of sort of freedom fighters in

01:21:19.820 --> 01:21:24.980
[Guest]: Kashmir, etc, then comes to be characterized as terrorism and sort of broadly not acceptable

01:21:24.980 --> 01:21:26.540
[Guest]: sort of behavior.

01:21:26.540 --> 01:21:30.020
[Guest]: And of course, you also have two other things which happened in that period, right, which

01:21:30.020 --> 01:21:35.220
[Guest]: is that you have an American President George W. Bush, who is, again, a very, you know,

01:21:35.220 --> 01:21:39.260
[Guest]: someone I feel had the American sort of ideology that we spoke about very, very strongly in

01:21:39.260 --> 01:21:40.260
[Guest]: his head.

01:21:40.260 --> 01:21:41.260
[Guest]: I mean, that's the way he used to think about the world, right.

01:21:41.260 --> 01:21:45.340
[Guest]: So for him, the world was about republics and democracies on the one side and others

01:21:45.340 --> 01:21:46.340
[Guest]: on the other side.

01:21:46.340 --> 01:21:50.660
[Guest]: So in a sense, that aspect of it allowed him to think of India as this very important kind

01:21:50.660 --> 01:21:52.060
[Guest]: of country and so on.

01:21:52.060 --> 01:21:55.980
[Guest]: The second thing which happens in the, you know, in the in the year around the sort of

01:21:55.980 --> 01:22:01.780
[Guest]: fixation with terrorism and other kinds of security threats is a wider sort of, you know,

01:22:01.780 --> 01:22:05.700
[Guest]: demographic change which is happening, which is the exponential growth of the Indian American

01:22:05.700 --> 01:22:08.100
[Guest]: community in the United States of America, right.

01:22:08.100 --> 01:22:11.540
[Guest]: And their extraordinary success in the United States, right.

01:22:11.540 --> 01:22:15.420
[Guest]: I mean, there's a new book edited by Devesh Kapoor and other colleagues called The Other

01:22:15.420 --> 01:22:19.300
[Guest]: One Percent, which is to say that, you know, the Indian Americans are actually the top

01:22:19.300 --> 01:22:21.900
[Guest]: one percent in of all immigrant communities.

01:22:21.900 --> 01:22:23.940
[Guest]: So Indians are living the American dream there.

01:22:23.940 --> 01:22:24.940
[Guest]: They are.

01:22:24.940 --> 01:22:26.940
[Guest]: I mean, and, you know, they're referred to as a model minority.

01:22:26.940 --> 01:22:30.540
[Guest]: Of course, you know, those kind of blanket terms always mask various kinds of differences

01:22:30.540 --> 01:22:31.540
[Guest]: and so on.

01:22:31.540 --> 01:22:35.180
[Guest]: But the reality is that, you know, the cultural impressions that Americans had of India, you

01:22:35.180 --> 01:22:39.980
[Guest]: know, which we've now spoken about at length, in some ways are dramatically changed in that

01:22:39.980 --> 01:22:40.980
[Guest]: decade.

01:22:40.980 --> 01:22:43.700
[Guest]: So I think, you know, while the activities of 9-11 were happening, there is also this

01:22:43.700 --> 01:22:49.640
[Guest]: background churn of migration, democracy, cultural change, which to me seems at least

01:22:49.640 --> 01:22:52.140
[Guest]: as important as the sort of surface events of terrorism.

01:22:52.140 --> 01:22:55.660
[Amit Varma]: So, I mean, the closeness of India and US, I mean, you can't turn the clock back.

01:22:55.660 --> 01:22:57.100
[Amit Varma]: It's there and it's just going to go deeper.

01:22:57.100 --> 01:22:58.100
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:22:58.100 --> 01:23:00.780
[Guest]: And I think, I mean, it can only turn back if American society itself changes, right.

01:23:00.780 --> 01:23:05.300
[Guest]: And in a sense, if we find, you know, sort of backlash against immigrants and such like

01:23:05.300 --> 01:23:08.620
[Guest]: things coming back, then we might be able to sort of say that, you know, yes, we're

01:23:08.620 --> 01:23:10.860
[Guest]: going to have a slightly more difficult period.

01:23:10.860 --> 01:23:15.980
[Guest]: But at this point of time, I'd say that, you know, some of those sort of longer term issues,

01:23:15.980 --> 01:23:20.020
[Guest]: which were so persistent, have undergone significant changes.

01:23:20.020 --> 01:23:23.420
[Guest]: And it's not clear to me that, you know, the clock is going to be turned back.

01:23:23.420 --> 01:23:27.260
[Amit Varma]: And what's also interesting is that while in the 80s, in the phase where they were supporting

01:23:27.260 --> 01:23:30.900
[Amit Varma]: India, I suppose they were tolerant of a lot that Pakistan did, especially with regard

01:23:30.900 --> 01:23:31.900
[Amit Varma]: to India.

01:23:31.900 --> 01:23:34.620
[Amit Varma]: But now they've called bullshit on Pakistan in various ways.

01:23:34.620 --> 01:23:37.740
[Amit Varma]: So you know, that dynamic is no longer there.

01:23:37.740 --> 01:23:43.040
[Guest]: Yes, but I would be sort of a little cautious about how we call that particular situation.

01:23:43.040 --> 01:23:46.700
[Guest]: Because the one thing which again, slightly longer term perspective suggests is that the

01:23:46.700 --> 01:23:50.580
[Guest]: United States and Pakistan have had pretty bad times as well as good times, right?

01:23:50.580 --> 01:23:54.260
[Guest]: I mean, they've been close, but they've also been sort of, they've been both best of friends

01:23:54.260 --> 01:23:55.260
[Guest]: and best of enemies.

01:23:55.260 --> 01:23:57.540
[Guest]: So, you know, in that sense, they've always had a...

01:23:57.540 --> 01:23:58.540
[Amit Varma]: It's like an abusive marriage.

01:23:58.540 --> 01:23:59.540
[Amit Varma]: It's like, I need you, but you keep lying to me.

01:23:59.540 --> 01:24:00.540
[Guest]: That is the Pakistani view, right?

01:24:00.540 --> 01:24:05.020
[Guest]: Pakistanis believe that Americans just use them and, you know, throw away, you know,

01:24:05.020 --> 01:24:09.620
[Guest]: as somebody said, colorfully once that, you know, in that sense, that's a Pakistani certainly

01:24:09.620 --> 01:24:10.620
[Amit Varma]: view.

01:24:10.620 --> 01:24:11.620
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I traveled through Pakistan in 2006.

01:24:11.620 --> 01:24:13.460
[Amit Varma]: And I was chatting with economists there.

01:24:13.460 --> 01:24:18.100
[Amit Varma]: And one of them said that all of them refer to Al-Qaeda as Al-Faida, because the Pakistani

01:24:18.100 --> 01:24:20.100
[Amit Varma]: state was basically failing in 2001.

01:24:20.100 --> 01:24:21.780
[Amit Varma]: When, you know, all that happened.

01:24:21.780 --> 01:24:25.660
[Amit Varma]: And suddenly American aid flooded back in and they kind of revived.

01:24:25.660 --> 01:24:30.580
[Guest]: So long as Americans are engaged in Afghanistan, and when I say engaged, I don't just mean

01:24:30.580 --> 01:24:34.060
[Guest]: military presence, but I find it difficult to understand how the United States is going

01:24:34.060 --> 01:24:36.220
[Guest]: to entirely pull out of a place like Afghanistan.

01:24:36.220 --> 01:24:41.300
[Guest]: You know, that area overlooks the backyard of China and Russia, in a sense, given their

01:24:41.300 --> 01:24:45.540
[Guest]: already existing military infrastructure presence, they might thin down, but I don't see them

01:24:45.540 --> 01:24:47.700
[Guest]: as giving up turning their backs on Afghanistan.

01:24:47.700 --> 01:24:52.020
[Guest]: You know, there's going to be no Vietnam like moment for Afghanistan, as far as I can see.

01:24:52.020 --> 01:24:54.980
[Guest]: So in that context, you know, having some degree of stability in Afghanistan will be

01:24:54.980 --> 01:24:56.420
[Guest]: an important concern.

01:24:56.420 --> 01:24:59.900
[Guest]: And I think one of the challenges that the Trump administration is going to face very

01:24:59.900 --> 01:25:04.660
[Guest]: soon is how are you going to have stability in Afghanistan, when you antagonize both Pakistan

01:25:04.660 --> 01:25:06.780
[Guest]: and Iran simultaneously, right?

01:25:06.780 --> 01:25:10.940
[Guest]: That seems to me to be a perfect recipe for having asking for trouble in Afghanistan.

01:25:10.940 --> 01:25:14.700
[Guest]: So you may well see a degree of modulation of policy towards Pakistan, which again, I

01:25:14.700 --> 01:25:15.700
[Guest]: would not be surprised.

01:25:15.700 --> 01:25:16.700
[Guest]: I mean, I'm

01:25:16.700 --> 01:25:17.700
[Guest]: Yeah, geopolitical.

01:25:17.700 --> 01:25:18.700
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:25:18.700 --> 01:25:22.700
[Guest]: So in a sense, you know, that that has happened so often now, that it is difficult to see.

01:25:22.700 --> 01:25:25.900
[Guest]: And I mean, you know, you would have imagined that if you if you want a sensible policy,

01:25:25.900 --> 01:25:30.540
[Guest]: you would say that, listen, the bigger threat is Pakistan sort of support for terrorism,

01:25:30.540 --> 01:25:34.760
[Guest]: especially in conjunction with nuclear weapons, you know, that the whole constellation of

01:25:34.760 --> 01:25:39.780
[Guest]: things which is so explosive out there, which if not controlled can get out of hand, you

01:25:39.780 --> 01:25:43.980
[Guest]: know, so it's better that we sort of, you know, keep Iran on the good side and, you

01:25:43.980 --> 01:25:45.300
[Guest]: know, try and put pressure on Pakistan.

01:25:45.300 --> 01:25:48.460
[Guest]: But then the Trump administration has chosen to tear up the one agreement they had with

01:25:48.460 --> 01:25:49.460
[Amit Varma]: Iran.

01:25:49.460 --> 01:25:53.100
[Amit Varma]: And we also now have a new elephant in the room, like how does the rise of China impact

01:25:53.100 --> 01:25:56.460
[Amit Varma]: the way the Cold War is over, the Soviets are not a factor, but how does how does the

01:25:56.460 --> 01:25:58.980
[Amit Varma]: rise of China impact the way America looks at this region?

01:25:58.980 --> 01:26:03.260
[Guest]: Well, I think it's it's it's going to be increasingly very important part, right?

01:26:03.260 --> 01:26:08.820
[Guest]: So US China relations, you know, are now I think we are now at a point where the Americans

01:26:08.820 --> 01:26:12.500
[Guest]: have more or less, you know, irrespective of the Trump administration, I think, you

01:26:12.500 --> 01:26:16.820
[Guest]: know, there's a broader understanding today in the United States that China is going to

01:26:16.820 --> 01:26:18.300
[Guest]: be the main competitor for us, right?

01:26:18.300 --> 01:26:22.700
[Guest]: Which I don't think was accepted quite as openly until now.

01:26:22.700 --> 01:26:25.780
[Guest]: But now even constituencies like businesses, which were always supportive of, you know,

01:26:25.780 --> 01:26:29.380
[Guest]: closer relations with China, understand and accept that, you know, Chinese practices are

01:26:29.380 --> 01:26:30.380
[Guest]: sort of the thing and so on.

01:26:30.380 --> 01:26:34.700
[Guest]: So I think I think, you know, you're now entering into a era where China will be seen as a peer

01:26:34.700 --> 01:26:36.740
[Guest]: competitor or at least a potential peer competitor.

01:26:36.740 --> 01:26:40.100
[Guest]: So you know, there is going to be a lot of circling of wagons against Chinese.

01:26:40.100 --> 01:26:44.020
[Guest]: Now, but at the same time, the China Pakistan relationship has been extremely strong over

01:26:44.020 --> 01:26:47.980
[Guest]: the past decade, you know, you've seen Chinese and Pakistanis coming together in very, very

01:26:47.980 --> 01:26:49.380
[Guest]: significant ways.

01:26:49.380 --> 01:26:51.980
[Guest]: And I think that trend is only going to get accelerated.

01:26:51.980 --> 01:26:53.500
[Guest]: But again, I would give credit for the Pakistanis, right?

01:26:53.500 --> 01:26:56.860
[Guest]: I mean, throughout the Cold War, they managed to keep the United States and China and even

01:26:56.860 --> 01:26:59.020
[Guest]: the Soviet Union on reasonably favorable terms, right?

01:26:59.020 --> 01:27:04.020
[Guest]: So for a country, you know, which, you know, has had other kinds of problems of various

01:27:04.020 --> 01:27:08.500
[Guest]: kinds, you know, they've managed to keep a reasonably creditable diplomatic act together.

01:27:08.500 --> 01:27:12.660
[Guest]: So I'd imagine that, you know, they'd be able to sort of work both sides of this.

01:27:12.660 --> 01:27:17.100
[Guest]: But I think as far as US India relations are concerned, definitely the rise of China and

01:27:17.100 --> 01:27:22.220
[Guest]: this kind of thing will will make for greater, you know, commonality of interest between

01:27:22.220 --> 01:27:26.380
[Guest]: the two sides in terms of managing that particular rise, in terms of ensuring that that rise

01:27:26.380 --> 01:27:29.800
[Guest]: is not destabilizing to the rest of the world, and so on.

01:27:29.800 --> 01:27:36.780
[Guest]: The larger question, however, I think, which is there before all of us is, to what extent

01:27:36.780 --> 01:27:42.460
[Guest]: does the sort of attitude taken by the Trump administration mark a historical sort of rupture

01:27:42.460 --> 01:27:46.900
[Guest]: from America's engagement with the subcontinent, at least since the onset of the Second World

01:27:46.900 --> 01:27:47.980
[Guest]: War, right?

01:27:47.980 --> 01:27:51.540
[Guest]: As we've discussed, I mean, the United States has had problems with countries like India,

01:27:51.540 --> 01:27:56.540
[Guest]: you know, on various kinds of dimensions, whether it's in foreign policy, economic issues,

01:27:56.540 --> 01:27:57.540
[Guest]: etc.

01:27:57.540 --> 01:28:01.140
[Guest]: But broadly speaking, the United States has believed that, you know, supporting countries

01:28:01.140 --> 01:28:03.260
[Guest]: like India is a larger geopolitical interest, right?

01:28:03.260 --> 01:28:08.180
[Guest]: Whether it was supporting India's five year plans, or, you know, its liberalization, whatever,

01:28:08.180 --> 01:28:11.100
[Guest]: even though they were unhappy with the pace of various kinds of things right up to date,

01:28:11.100 --> 01:28:12.100
[Guest]: right?

01:28:12.100 --> 01:28:15.220
[Guest]: I mean, in a sense, there has been analysts like Ashley Tellis say, degree of strategic

01:28:15.220 --> 01:28:17.700
[Guest]: altruism as far as the United States is concerned.

01:28:17.700 --> 01:28:21.100
[Guest]: There has been an assumption, at least under the Bush and Obama administrations, that the

01:28:21.100 --> 01:28:24.740
[Guest]: rise of India in some ways is automatically an American good, whether Indians actually

01:28:24.740 --> 01:28:26.860
[Guest]: do anything for America or not.

01:28:26.860 --> 01:28:29.240
[Guest]: Now, Donald Trump clearly takes a very different view.

01:28:29.240 --> 01:28:32.820
[Guest]: He wants people to do things for America because he believes they owe the United States.

01:28:32.820 --> 01:28:35.660
[Amit Varma]: He has a zero sum view of the world and everything is transactional.

01:28:35.660 --> 01:28:41.140
[Guest]: So yeah, so in a sense, it's and in that sense, I think, if the Trump phenomenon proves to

01:28:41.140 --> 01:28:45.260
[Guest]: be durable, which is to say that, you know, it is more than just the passing whimsy of

01:28:45.260 --> 01:28:50.180
[Guest]: one particular politician who has managed to capture power by whatever reasons.

01:28:50.180 --> 01:28:52.900
[Guest]: That could then mark a very different set of things, right?

01:28:52.900 --> 01:28:58.140
[Guest]: Because that then marks a certain kind of disengagement or a reorientation of America's

01:28:58.140 --> 01:29:01.900
[Guest]: position in the world, which is very different from everything that the United States did

01:29:01.900 --> 01:29:03.900
[Guest]: in the post Second World War period, right?

01:29:03.900 --> 01:29:06.260
[Guest]: And it's in that sense that, you know, I think when Americans say that, you know, is the

01:29:06.260 --> 01:29:08.420
[Guest]: liberal international order coming to an end and so on.

01:29:08.420 --> 01:29:11.260
[Guest]: There's a lot of debate currently about that stuff.

01:29:11.260 --> 01:29:14.300
[Guest]: People tend to argue about whether or was it a liberal order, etc.

01:29:14.300 --> 01:29:18.100
[Guest]: But I think the bottom line point is this, which is that when the United States came

01:29:18.100 --> 01:29:22.540
[Guest]: into the Second World War, it took a certain view of its position in the world, which was

01:29:22.540 --> 01:29:27.380
[Guest]: to say that if we want to be the global sort of leader and hegemon, then we need to be

01:29:27.380 --> 01:29:31.900
[Guest]: able to take asymmetric costs for that kind of leadership position, both economically,

01:29:31.900 --> 01:29:34.260
[Guest]: in security terms, political terms, and so on.

01:29:34.260 --> 01:29:38.260
[Guest]: Now with the Trump administration, those assumptions are under question, because here it believes

01:29:38.260 --> 01:29:39.880
[Amit Varma]: that everyone is ripping off America.

01:29:39.880 --> 01:29:45.380
[Amit Varma]: Is he the first president who's actually thrust aside that sense of manifest destiny?

01:29:45.380 --> 01:29:48.780
[Guest]: Not really, you know, there have been previous American presidents who have confronted very

01:29:48.780 --> 01:29:49.960
[Guest]: similar kinds of dilemmas.

01:29:49.960 --> 01:29:52.900
[Guest]: And I think the person who confronted it in the starkest terms in some ways was Richard

01:29:52.900 --> 01:29:53.900
[Guest]: Nixon.

01:29:53.900 --> 01:29:54.900
[Guest]: Because you think about it, right?

01:29:54.900 --> 01:29:59.300
[Guest]: When Richard Nixon becomes president in 1969, the United States is in this long war in Vietnam,

01:29:59.300 --> 01:30:00.660
[Guest]: which is going nowhere.

01:30:00.660 --> 01:30:05.900
[Guest]: The American sort of economy is under terrible strain, partly because of its military expenditure

01:30:05.900 --> 01:30:10.820
[Guest]: in Vietnam, but also this whole sort of pegging the dollar to the gold, which was the old

01:30:10.820 --> 01:30:13.260
[Guest]: Bretton Woods order is kind of coming up, right?

01:30:13.260 --> 01:30:14.260
[Guest]: And what is the Nixon administration's response?

01:30:14.260 --> 01:30:17.420
[Guest]: Nixon's administration's response is one to unilaterally get out of the Bretton Woods

01:30:17.420 --> 01:30:19.140
[Guest]: order in 1971, right?

01:30:19.140 --> 01:30:23.740
[Guest]: With zero notice to anyone, just one fine day say, sorry, convertibility of dollar and

01:30:23.740 --> 01:30:24.740
[Guest]: gold no longer exists.

01:30:24.740 --> 01:30:27.820
[Guest]: We are now in a world of free floating exchange rates, which is as big a shock as you can

01:30:27.820 --> 01:30:30.740
[Guest]: give to the global economy as anything could be.

01:30:30.740 --> 01:30:33.740
[Guest]: The second thing he says is the so-called Nixon doctrine, where he says that American

01:30:33.740 --> 01:30:38.420
[Guest]: allies will now have to start taking sort of contributing more towards their own security.

01:30:38.420 --> 01:30:39.940
[Guest]: You cannot expect the United States to do, right?

01:30:39.940 --> 01:30:42.540
[Guest]: So it's not very different from what Donald Trump is saying.

01:30:42.540 --> 01:30:45.900
[Guest]: But the reality was that people like Nixon, Kissinger, Howard never believed that the

01:30:45.900 --> 01:30:50.220
[Guest]: United States had to, you know, basically do transactional deals with everyone around,

01:30:50.220 --> 01:30:51.220
[Guest]: right?

01:30:51.220 --> 01:30:52.220
[Guest]: Or to expect reciprocity from everyone, right?

01:30:52.220 --> 01:30:56.860
[Guest]: See, for a country like India, I think the problem is this, that when you see the United

01:30:56.860 --> 01:31:03.580
[Guest]: States dealing in this fashion with allies like Canada, or Germany, or Japan, then as

01:31:03.580 --> 01:31:09.420
[Guest]: a country which is, you know, still very decidedly non-allied to the United States, what do you

01:31:09.420 --> 01:31:11.980
[Guest]: expect to happen to you, right?

01:31:11.980 --> 01:31:14.720
[Guest]: And I think the prognosis in some ways is going to be a bit mixed, right?

01:31:14.720 --> 01:31:18.620
[Guest]: You can never be too sure that, you know, you won't get caught in the crosshairs or

01:31:18.620 --> 01:31:19.620
[Guest]: some kind of a thing.

01:31:19.620 --> 01:31:23.740
[Guest]: And, you know, for instance, this whole obsession with, you know, every trade relationship has

01:31:23.740 --> 01:31:24.740
[Guest]: to be balanced.

01:31:24.740 --> 01:31:26.740
[Guest]: I mean, you know, that's the most extraordinary way of thinking about it.

01:31:26.740 --> 01:31:28.300
[Guest]: Yeah, but but it's there, right?

01:31:28.300 --> 01:31:29.660
[Guest]: I mean, he's doing it to everyone.

01:31:29.660 --> 01:31:32.380
[Guest]: I mean, again, you know, just now they've given notice to Japan.

01:31:32.380 --> 01:31:35.860
[Guest]: And he said in a press conference that India has agreed that they're going to begin talks

01:31:35.860 --> 01:31:36.860
[Guest]: and so on.

01:31:36.860 --> 01:31:37.860
[Guest]: I don't know what has been agreed.

01:31:37.860 --> 01:31:39.660
[Guest]: But, you know, those things are coming.

01:31:39.660 --> 01:31:44.420
[Guest]: So it will make for a pretty interesting and challenging period for us to navigate.

01:31:44.420 --> 01:31:45.420
[Amit Varma]: To say the least.

01:31:45.420 --> 01:31:48.500
[Amit Varma]: So in this episode, I've taken up more than 90 minutes of your time, and we've already

01:31:48.500 --> 01:31:51.540
[Amit Varma]: sort of reached the present day, which is the end of history.

01:31:51.540 --> 01:31:57.900
[Amit Varma]: So I'm going to ask you to end by sort of asking you a question with two parts, which

01:31:57.900 --> 01:32:05.540
[Amit Varma]: is instead of looking back, look forward and tell me that from a vantage point of 2028,

01:32:05.540 --> 01:32:10.140
[Amit Varma]: what is the best case scenario and the worst case scenario of American involvement in South

01:32:10.140 --> 01:32:11.140
[Amit Varma]: Asia?

01:32:11.140 --> 01:32:18.580
[Guest]: Well, what is the best case scenario is that you have a situation in Afghanistan, which

01:32:18.580 --> 01:32:22.940
[Guest]: is not much worse than what you have right now, in a sense, winning the war against the

01:32:22.940 --> 01:32:26.420
[Guest]: Taliban with the kind of commitment that they want to make.

01:32:26.420 --> 01:32:29.140
[Amit Varma]: But you see it as an ongoing thing, not won the war, winning the war.

01:32:29.140 --> 01:32:30.140
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:32:30.140 --> 01:32:34.260
[Guest]: So in a sense, it will be an ongoing issue of management of the problem, right?

01:32:34.260 --> 01:32:37.220
[Guest]: See, my own sense is, you know, Donald Trump was definitely not the first president to

01:32:37.220 --> 01:32:38.220
[Guest]: deal with these problems.

01:32:38.220 --> 01:32:39.540
[Guest]: He's not going to be the last president, right?

01:32:39.540 --> 01:32:43.980
[Guest]: Because many of these issues are issues that stem from the region's own problems.

01:32:43.980 --> 01:32:46.860
[Guest]: There is only so much that any American administration can do.

01:32:46.860 --> 01:32:49.780
[Guest]: So they can either work with the grain or against the grain.

01:32:49.780 --> 01:32:53.020
[Guest]: The best hope is that, you know, you can manage the problems rather than solve them, right?

01:32:53.020 --> 01:32:56.860
[Guest]: So in that sense, if you're able to sort of keep some degree of stability in Afghanistan

01:32:56.860 --> 01:33:03.120
[Guest]: going, if you can prevent Pakistan from say, you know, going further down the route of

01:33:03.120 --> 01:33:09.500
[Guest]: terrorism support for that kind of infrastructure, you know, ensure that political sort of leadership,

01:33:09.500 --> 01:33:13.500
[Guest]: leadership in Pakistan slowly gets some degree of, you know, strength within their system

01:33:13.500 --> 01:33:14.620
[Guest]: and so on.

01:33:14.620 --> 01:33:19.180
[Guest]: And you have a relationship with India, which kind of continues to improve.

01:33:19.180 --> 01:33:23.340
[Guest]: And I think the improvement is not just in security terms, but I think also in economic

01:33:23.340 --> 01:33:24.900
[Amit Varma]: terms, I think that that's going to be a...

01:33:24.900 --> 01:33:26.980
[Amit Varma]: Okay, your best case is incredibly boring.

01:33:26.980 --> 01:33:27.980
[Guest]: What's the worst case?

01:33:27.980 --> 01:33:28.980
[Guest]: Yeah, what are the worst case?

01:33:28.980 --> 01:33:33.140
[Guest]: The worst case is that, you know, you have, you could end up with a series of sort of

01:33:33.140 --> 01:33:36.860
[Guest]: conflicts between Afghanistan, Pakistan, or Pakistan and India.

01:33:36.860 --> 01:33:39.540
[Guest]: One of which have to be sort of traditional wars of the kinds that happened in the past,

01:33:39.540 --> 01:33:41.980
[Guest]: though, you know, nobody can rule out those kinds of things.

01:33:41.980 --> 01:33:46.900
[Guest]: But various kinds of challenges for which the United States doesn't have really the

01:33:46.900 --> 01:33:50.460
[Guest]: capacity to intervene in the way that it was able to do in the past, right?

01:33:50.460 --> 01:33:55.060
[Guest]: I mean, to me, the most important challenge, I mean, forget 2028, but even today would

01:33:55.060 --> 01:34:00.060
[Guest]: be that, does the Trump administration really have the understanding, attention span and

01:34:00.060 --> 01:34:03.900
[Guest]: interest to be able to engage with the subcontinent if you have, say, a crisis like what happened

01:34:03.900 --> 01:34:06.740
[Guest]: in 2001 and 2002, like when there was a serious attack on India, right?

01:34:06.740 --> 01:34:10.220
[Guest]: I mean, of that scale or something around the scale of 2008.

01:34:10.220 --> 01:34:15.660
[Guest]: I mean, what do we expect Americans to sort of really be able to do in that context, given

01:34:15.660 --> 01:34:20.660
[Guest]: how depleted diplomatic resources are in this administration, and so on, right?

01:34:20.660 --> 01:34:25.020
[Guest]: So in that sense, I think a lot depends on whether the current trends continue up to

01:34:25.020 --> 01:34:26.620
[Guest]: 2028 or not in the United States, right?

01:34:26.620 --> 01:34:29.620
[Guest]: I mean, if things take a turn for the better, then you know, you're always going to be this

01:34:29.620 --> 01:34:30.620
[Guest]: thing.

01:34:30.620 --> 01:34:34.260
[Guest]: But at this point of time, I think, as you said, you know, the best case scenario is

01:34:34.260 --> 01:34:38.900
[Guest]: that you sort of more or less continue to chug along the same lines, which is more of

01:34:38.900 --> 01:34:40.020
[Guest]: the same.

01:34:40.020 --> 01:34:43.180
[Guest]: And the worst case scenario is that you have crises that the United States is not able

01:34:43.180 --> 01:34:48.060
[Guest]: to manage in any meaningful way, in looked upon in a historical baseline, right?

01:34:48.060 --> 01:34:51.660
[Guest]: I mean, looked upon, say, from the baseline of 1962, when you had the Cuban Missile Crisis

01:34:51.660 --> 01:34:56.540
[Guest]: going on, but still, you were able to do some things when you had a problem in the subcontinent.

01:34:56.540 --> 01:34:58.260
[Amit Varma]: So the best case scenario is more of the same.

01:34:58.260 --> 01:35:00.060
[Amit Varma]: And we are all still here in 2028.

